ntre' as part of financial inclusion initiatives\n<br />\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Banks}}\n*[[Banking in India]]\n*[[List of banks in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Banking in India}}\n\n[[Category:Public Sector Banks in India]]\n[[Category:Banks based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Companies nationalised by the Government of India]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n", "name_user": "Aki4uuu", "label": "safe", "comment": "citation added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Union_Bank_of_India"}
{"title_page": "Dawood Ibrahim", "text_new": "{{short description|Mumbai monster, drug dealer, and terrorist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{cleanup|reason=conflicting places of birth.|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Dawood Ibrahim \n| image = \n| birth_name = Dawood Ibrahim Kaskar\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1955|12|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Khed, Ratnagiri|Khed]], [[Bombay State]], India\n\n \n| occupation = Child abuser,Gangster and drug dealer\n| organization = [[D-Company]]\n| net_worth = {{Estimation}} US$ 200 million (May 2015)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dawood Ibrahim is the 2nd richest gangster of all time|url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-pakistan-karachi/1/941579.html|website=[[India Today]]|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n| spouse = Mehjabeen Shaikh (aka Zubeena Zareen)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/its-official-again-ahead-of-nsa-talks-fresh-photo-passport-copy-of-dawood-confirm-hes-in-pakistan-2403302.html|title=It is official: Ahead of NSA meet, fresh photo and passport copy of Dawood Ibrahim confirm he's in Pakistan|work=Firstpost}}</ref>\n| criminal_charge = [[Organised crime]], [[drug trafficking]], [[extortion]], [[targeted killing]], [[terrorism]]\n| wanted_by = India\n| wanted_since = 1994\n| opponents = {{Collapsible list\n|title = At least 4\n| 1 = [[Gang wars between Chota Rajan and Dawood Ibrahim|Rajan Nikalje]]\n| 2 = [[Ali Budesh#Open war with Dawood Ibrahim|Ali Budesh]]\n| 3 = Ejaz Lakdawal\n| 4 = [[Arun Gawli#Criminal activities|Arun Gawli]]\n}}\n| children = 3\n| relatives = [[Shabir Ibrahim Kaskar]] (brother); (deceased)<br />Iqbal Ibrahim Kaskar (brother)<br />[[Haseena Parkar]] (sister);(deceased)\n| nationality = Indian\n}}\n'''Dawood Ibrahim Kaskar''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-us-Dawood_Ibrahim_from_India_pronunciation_(Voice_of_America).ogg |\u026a|b|r|\u0259|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|m}}; born 26 December 1955) is a [[Organised crime in India#Mumbai underworld|Mumbai underworld figure]], criminal mobster,phedophile,coward and drug dealer, most wanted by India with a reward of $250 billion<ref name=\"reward\">{{cite web|title=3 students forced to end their 'Dawood hunt' after money runs out|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/3-students-forced-to-end-their-dawood-hunt-after-money-runs-out-1373291.html/amp|website=[[First Post]]|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> over his head, and has been wanted since 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://keralakaumudi.com/en/news/news.php?id=111752&u=new-evidence-proves-dawood-ibrahim-hiding-in-pakistans-karachi-111752|title=New evidence proves Dawood Ibrahim hiding in Pakistan's Karachi|last=Daily|first=Keralakaumudi|website=Keralakaumudi Daily|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> He is originally from [[Dongri]] in [[Mumbai]], India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/jl9742.aspx|title=Treasury Sanctions Two Indian Nationals and a Company Based in Pakistan for Ties to the South Asian Criminal Network \u2018D Company\u2019|website=www.treasury.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sc/suborg/en/sanctions/1267/aq_sanctions_list/summaries/individual/dawood-ibrahim-kaskar|title=DAWOOD IBRAHIM KASKAR {{!}} United Nations Security Council Subsidiary Organs|website=www.un.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref>\n\nHe is a friend of crashing bollywood actor [[Sanjay Dutt]] and infant father of [[Rishi Kapoor]] and is currently believed to be hiding in Pakistan, according to the Indian government,and is last seen by [[Salman Khan]] in 2016, but he asked $20 million in return,which government refused to pay but rather made a deal to make 1000 Bollywood films with him,where he plays the same role of do-all good powerful guy<ref name=\"ind-exp-inpakistan\"/> and heads the Indian [[organised crime]] syndicate [[D-Company]] which he founded in [[Mumbai]] in the 1970s.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/article3093209.ece The name on the Mumbai street over terror attacks is Dawood Ibrahim.] ''The Times''. 13 July 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim Kaskar |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/dawood-ibrahim-kaskar/|newspaper=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/international/21583285-growth-slows-and-reforms-falter-economic-activity-shifting-out-india-made-outside|title=Made outside India|website=The Economist|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/24/opinion/fix-the-link-to-pakistan-bond-with-india.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Fix the Link to Pakistan, Bond With India|last=Kugelman|first=Michael|date=2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/dec/02/mumbai-most-wanted|title=India names two most-wanted fugitives after Mumbai attacks|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=2008-12-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Dawood is wanted on the charges of [[murder]], [[extortion]], [[targeted killing]], [[drug trafficking]], [[terrorism]] and various other cases. He was designated as a global terrorist in 2003 by India and the United States with a reward of US$25 million for his capture for his believed role in the [[1993 Bombay bombings]].<ref name=\"reward\"/><ref name=Interpol>{{cite web |title=Shaikh, Dawood Hasan |publisher=[[Interpol]] |url=http://www.interpol.int/Wanted-Persons/%28wanted_id%29/1993-14193 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20121212010010/http://www.interpol.int/Wanted-Persons/(wanted_id)/1993-14193 |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=30 December 2012 }}</ref> In 2011, he was named number three on \"The World's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives\" by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Henley |first1=Jon |title=Who is now on the World's Most Wanted list? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/may/04/the-worlds-most-wanted-list |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> and [[Forbes]].<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2011/06/14/most-wanted-fugitives_slide_4.html \"Dawood 4th 'most wanted' criminal on Forbes list\"]. ''Forbes''. (29 April 2008). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDawood Ibrahim was born on 26 December 1955 in a [[Konkani Muslim]] family in [[Ratnagiri]] in  [[Maharashtra]], India.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 things to know about Dawood Ibrahim|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/inia-news/10-things-to-know-about-dawood-ibrahim/article1-1344167.aspx|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref>  His father, Ibrahim Kaskar, worked as a head constable with the [[Mumbai Police]] and his mother, Amina, was a homemaker.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Swami|first=Praveen|date=9 April 1999|title=Mumbai's mafia wars|url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1607/16070420.htm|journal=[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]]|volume=16|issue=7|access-date=23 August 2015}}</ref>\nHe lived in the Temkar Mohalla area of Dongri,  attended Ahmed Sailor High School from which he dropped out.\nHe grew up in the [[Dongri]] locality of Mumbai, which was when he came in contact with the gang of mobster [[Haji Mastan]], after the latter attacked two of Ibrahim's men.<ref>{{cite news|title='Dongri to Dubai,' the rise of Dawood Ibrahim|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/books/dongri-to-dubai-the-rise-of-dawood-ibrahim-484211.html|accessdate=23 August 2015|work=CNN-IBN|date=25 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIbrahim is believed to control much of the [[hawala]] system, which is the very commonly used [[informal value transfer system|unofficial system for transferring money]] and remittances outside the view of official agents. Many of the organisation's operations are in India.<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20001231/main1.htm Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2013 Main News]. ''The Tribune''. (31 December 2000). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/2002/dec/22isi.htm 'ISI pressured Dawood to carry out Mumbai blasts']. Rediff.com (22 December 2002). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Department of the Treasury]] [[Office of Foreign Assets Control#Specially Designated Nationals List|designated]] Ibrahim as a terrorist as part of its international sanctions program, effectively forbidding US financial entities from working with him and seizing assets believed to be under his control. The Department of Treasury keeps a fact sheet on Ibrahim which contains reports of his syndicate having smuggling routes from South Asia, the Middle-East and Africa shared with and used by terrorist organization [[al-Qaeda]]. The fact sheet also said that Ibrahim's syndicate is involved in large-scale shipment of narcotics in the United Kingdom and Western Europe. He is also believed to have had contacts with al-Qaeda leader [[Osama bin-Laden]]. In the late 1990s, Ibrahim traveled to [[Afghanistan]] under the [[Taliban]]'s protection. The syndicate has consistently aimed to destabilise the Indian government through riots, terrorism and civil disobedience.<ref>{{cite news |title=Possible al-Qaida link to India train attacks |publisher=[[NBC News]] |author=Robert Windrem |date=11 July 2006 |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/13815413 |accessdate=10 April 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe US stated that it will request the United Nations to list Ibrahim \"in pursuance of relevant Security Council resolutions\". Such a UN listing will require that all UN member states freeze Ibrahim's assets and impose a travel ban. Juan Zarate, the Deputy Assistant Secretary for Terrorist Financing and Financial Crimes, said that they are committed to identifying and attacking financial ties between terrorism and the underworld.<ref name=\"Rediff\"/>\nIbrahim is also suspected to have connections with terrorist organisations, and in 2002 was linked to the financing of increasing attacks in [[Gujarat]] by [[Lashkar-e-Toiba]].<ref name=\"Rediff\"/> In 2006, the government of India handed over to Pakistan, a list of 38 most wanted criminals including Ibrahim.<ref name=\"ID\">{{cite news|title=Bush administration imposes sanctions on India's most wanted criminals Dawood Ibrahim and sai bansod |publisher=IndiaDaily |date=2 June 2006 |url=http://www.indiadaily.com/editorial/9367.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212112236/http://www.indiadaily.com/editorial/9367.asp |archivedate=12 February 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 November 2006, it was reported that ten members of Ibrahim's gang were arrested by the Crime Branch of Mumbai Police. They were extradited from the [[United Arab Emirates]], from where they had been deported.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dubai extradites 10 Dawood aides |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=21 November 2006 |url=http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/nov/21arrest.htm |accessdate=10 April 2007 }}</ref>\n\n''[[India Today]]'' reported that Ibrahim provided the logistics for the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]].<ref>[http://indiatoday.digitaltoday.in/index.php?option=com_content&issueid=81&task=view&id=21254&sectionid=4&Itemid=1 India Today] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201082310/http://indiatoday.digitaltoday.in/index.php?option=com_content&issueid=81&task=view&id=21254&sectionid=4&Itemid=1 |date=1 December 2008 }}. Indiatoday.digitaltoday.in (28 November 2008). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref>\n\nNews media outlets reported the murder of Shiraz Asghar Ali as a sign of a dramatic shift of power between the crime lords.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vivo ipl schedule live |work=[[The Week]] |author1=Dnyanesh Jathar |author2=Quaied Najmi |date=2 February 2003 |url=http://www.the-week.com/23feb02/events11.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316063733/http://www.the-week.com/23feb02/events11.htm |archivedate=16 March 2007 |accessdate=10 April 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe Nepal government has directed freezing of assets of 224 individuals and 64 groups with Ibrahim if they are present in Nepal under Nepal's Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indistannews.com/nepal-freezes-assets-of-entities-with-dawood-al-qaeda-links/ |title=Nepal freezes assets of entities with Dawood, Al Qaeda links |publisher=Indistan News |date=26 December 1955 |accessdate=12 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229163322/http://www.indistannews.com/nepal-freezes-assets-of-entities-with-dawood-al-qaeda-links/ |archivedate=29 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, former Indian cricketer [[Dilip Vengsarkar]] alleged that in 1986, Dawood had entered the Indian team dressing room in [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]] and offered each Indian player a car if they beat Pakistan in the Sharjah Cup final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/top-stories/Dawood-entered-Indian-dressing-room-in-1986-offered-cars-to-players-Vengsarkar/articleshow/24822450.cms |title=Dawood entered Indian dressing room in 1986, offered cars to players: Vengsarkar |work=The Times of India |date=28 October 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==1993 Bombay bombings==\n{{Expand section|date=May 2017}}\nDawood is widely believed to have masterminded the [[1993 Bombay bombings|March 1993 bombings in Bombay]]. In 2003, the Indian and United States governments declared Ibrahim a \"Global Terrorist.\" The Indian Deputy Prime Minister, [[L. K. Advani|Lal Krishna Advani]] described it as a major development. Ibrahim is currently on India's \"Most Wanted List\".<ref name=\"Rediff\">{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim is a global terrorist: US |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=17 October 2003 |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2003/oct/17daw.htm |accessdate=10 April 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn a public discourse in June 2017, [[Ram Jethmalani]] confirmed that after the Bombay blasts, Dawood Ibrahim had called him from [[London]], saying that he was prepared to come to India and stand trial, on the condition that he should not be subjected to any [[Third-degree methods|third degree]] treatment from the police.<ref name=\"algebra\">{{cite web |title=The legend of Ram&nbsp;\u2013 a conversation with Ram Jethmalani |url=http://www.algebratheclub.com/event/the-legend-of-ram/ |website=Algebra talks |publisher=Algebra |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref>   Jethmalani had conveyed this to [[Sharad Pawar]], but the politicians in power did not agree to this proposal. As per Jethmalani, their refusal to allow Dawood's return was due to their fears that he would expose their secrets.<ref name=\"it\">{{cite magazine |title=Ram Jethmalani, Sharad Pawar spar over Dawood Ibrahim |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/dawood-ibrahim-surrender-ram-jethmalani-sharad-pawar-spar-280635-2015-07-04 |accessdate=13 June 2018 |magazine=India Today |date=4 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sharad Pawar: Jethmalani\u2019s proposal on Dawood Ibrahim was conditional |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/ram-jethmalanis-proposal-on-dawood-was-conditional-sharad-pawar/ |accessdate=13 June 2018 |newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nAccording to International claims, Ibrahim is believed to be living in [[Pakistan]] and then in the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.in.com/news/current-affairs/bdawood-ibrahim-was-in-pak-till-april-2013-ipl-spotfixing-chargesheetb-50243851-in-1.html |title=Dawood Ibrahim was in Pak till April 2013: IPL spot-fixing chargesheet |publisher=In.com |accessdate=12 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319043200/http://www.in.com/news/current-affairs/bdawood-ibrahim-was-in-pak-till-april-2013-ipl-spotfixing-chargesheetb-50243851-in-1.html |archive-date=19 March 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Desk |first=Web |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/588663/dawood-ibrahim-chased-out-of-pakistan-pms-special-envoy/ |title=Dawood Ibrahim chased out of Pakistan: PM\u2019s special envoy |work=The Express Tribune |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/cnnibn-videos/413193/time-crunch-10082013.html |title=Dawood Ibrahim was in Pak till April 2013: IPL spot-fixing chargesheet-CNN-IBN |publisher=IBNLive |date=10 August 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dawood-ibrahim-was-here-but-we-chased-him-out-may-be-in-uae-now-shahryar-khan/1153581/ |title=Dawood Ibrahim was here but we chased him out, may be in UAE now: Shahryar Khan |work=The Indian Express |date=10 August 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref> According to Indian claims he has shifted to the Pakistan-Afghanistan border. Indian sources add that \"[[Inter-Services Intelligence]] appeared extremely wary of the new Indo-US cooperation to fight terrorism. The Inter-Services Intelligence and Dawood appear under a lot of pressure\"<ref>{{cite web|author=ET Bureau |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/44943006.cms |title=ISI shifts underworld don Dawood Ibrahim to Pakistan-Afghanistan border&nbsp;\u2014 timesofindia-economictimes |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-10-27 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref>\nOn 5 May 2015 MP [[Haribhai Chaudhary]] informed the [[Lok Sabha]] (the [[lower house]] of India's Parliament) that the whereabouts of Ibrahim were unknown.<ref name=\"ind-exp-inpakistan\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim Whereabouts |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/videos/india/former-officers-contradict-centres-claim-of-dawood-ibrahim-being-untraceable-congress-sees-red-987622.html |newspaper=IBN Live}}</ref> However, on 11 May, [[Rajnath Singh]], the then [[Home Minister of India]], told the parliament that Ibrahim was in Pakistan and he will bring him back to India.<ref name=\"ind-exp-inpakistan\">{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim is in Pakistan, Rajnath assures Lok Sabha |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/dawood-ibrahim-is-in-pakistan-rajnath-assures-lok-sabha/ |accessdate=19 May 2015 |newspaper=Indian Express |date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood in Pakistan, Will Get Him No Matter What: Rajnath Singh in Parliament |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/dawood-in-pakistan-will-get-him-no-matter-what-rajnath-singh-in-parliament-762125 |accessdate=19 May 2015 |publisher=NDTV |date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood in pakistan |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/dawood-is-in-pakistan-india-will-leave-no-stone-unturned-to-bring-him-back-rajnath/article1-1345945.aspx |accessdate=19 May 2015 |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Rajnath says Dawood is in Pakistan|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-rajnath-singh-pakistan/1/437341.html |accessdate=19 May 2015 |magazine=India Today|date=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to claims of Indian news media ''[[Times Now]]'' on 22 August 2015, Dawood was in [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]. According to said media corporation, they had conversation with a woman in Karachi on August 22, 2015. Transcripts of conversations which were published on the news agency's website, in one conversation she said that she is Dawood's wife and \"he is sleeping\", while in the second conversation she said that there was no one by that name known to her.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Times News Network |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Dawoods-wife-confirms-her-husband-is-in-Karachi/articleshow/48616473.cms |title=Dawood's wife confirms her husband is in Karachi&nbsp;\u2014 The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=August 22, 2015 |accessdate=2015-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesnow.tv/videoshow/4479776.cms |title=TIMES NOW tracks Dawood Ibrahim-News-Exclusives-TIMESNOW.tv&nbsp;\u2014 Latest Breaking News, Big News Stories, News Videos |publisher=Timesnow.tv |date= |accessdate=2015-08-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824080224/http://www.timesnow.tv/videoshow/4479776.cms |archive-date=24 August 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a dossier prepared by India in August 2015, to be handed over to Pakistan, Ibrahim has nine residences in Pakistan and has three Pakistani passports which he frequently uses to travel.<ref>{{cite web|title = Dawood Ibrahim has nine residences in Pakistan, Delhi says|url = http://gulfnews.com/news/asia/pakistan/dawood-ibrahim-has-nine-residences-in-pakistan-delhi-says-1.1571342|website = gulfnews.com|accessdate = 2015-08-24}}</ref>\n\n== Search for Dawood Ibrahim ==\nHe has been on [[The World's 10 Most Wanted]] list since 2010, and third in the list,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/05/13/bin-laden-joaquin-guzman-dawood-ibrahim-business-world-most-wanted.html|title=The World's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives|last1=Vardi|first1=Nathan|website=Forbes|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref> and is designated a \"global terrorist\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2003/oct/17daw.htm|title=Dawood Ibrahim is a global terrorist: US|date=17 October 2003|work=Rediff|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref> Many attempts have been made to locate Ibrahim by the Indian intelligence agencies, [[Research and Analysis Wing]] and [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] (IB), ever since he went into hiding. His location has been frequently traced to [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]], a claim which the Pakistani authorities have frequently denied.<ref name=\"BanksNevers2007\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g2UXBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT113|title=Combating Terrorism: Strategies and Approaches|author1=William C. Banks|author2=Ren\u00e9e de Nevers|author3=Mitchel B. Wallerstein|date=1 October 2007|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4833-7092-7|page=113}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/oct/19pakpoll1.htm|title=Pakistan denies Dawood's presence on its soil|date=19 October 2007|work=Rediff|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/envoy-denies-dawoods-presence-in-pakistan/article7195012.ece|title=Envoy denies Dawood\u2019s presence in Pakistan|last1=Khan|first1=Atiq|date=12 May 2015|work=The Hindu|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-sanjay-dutt-1993-mumbai-blasts--pakistan/1/258887.html|title=Exclusive: This is where Dawood lives in Karachi. A la Osama, the Pakistanis don't know!|date=22 March 2013|work=India Today|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/raw-report-on-terrorist-dawood-pakistan-stay-shows-he-was-not-chased-out/1/298998.html|title=Pakistan's Dawood lie nailed! RAW report on terrorist's Pak stay shows he wasn't chased out of country|date=11 August 2013|work=India Today|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref> The claims were further established in August 2015, when a phone call made to his home by an Indian television channel, ''[[Times Now]]'', was answered by his wife, who confirmed his presence at their home in Karachi. The Indian intelligence agencies immediately prepared a [[Dossier criminal|dossier]] of Ibrahim which included evidence of his location in Karachi, among other evidence. It was to be presented at the [[National Security Agency]]-level talks between the two countries in the same month, which was however, called off due to political reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/dawood-ibrahim-purchased-property-close-to-bhutto-sons-house-in-2013/article7569182.ece|title=Indian dossier lists don Dawood Ibrahim\u2019s Pakistan assets|last1=Singh|first1=Vijaota|date=23 August 2015|work=The Hindu|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/india-has-evidence-of-dawood-ibrahim-living-in-pakistan-report/|title=Dawood Ibrahim\u2019s new home in Karachi near Bilawal\u2019s residence|last1=Chowdhury|first1=Sagnik|date=23 August 2013|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[India Today]]'', [[Chhota Rajan]], a former aide of Ibrahim, who he later fell out with in 1992, said that, \"He [Ibrahim] does travel out of Pakistan once in a while but Karachi is his base.\"<ref>{{cite journal|date=31 January 1996|title='I gave the instructions for Wahid's killing'|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/i-will-return-to-india-and-face-trial-but-after-teaching-dawood-a-lesson-says-chhota-rajan/1/281836.html|journal=[[India Today]]|access-date=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Chhota Rajan vs Dawood Ibrahim==\n[[Chhota Rajan]] is believed to have assisted intelligence agencies in getting a low down on the activities of the [[D-Company]] and its members by using his intimate knowledge of the criminal enterprise and its operations from his experience. To reinforce his reputation as a patriotic gangster don, Chhota Rajan threatened to brutally murder those accused of engineering the [[1993 Mumbai bombings]].<ref>[https://scroll.in/article/764928/the-patriotic-don-chhota-rajan-was-said-to-be-helping-india-find-dawood-ibrahim Chhota Rajan, The \u2018Patriotic Don\u2019] - Scroll.IN Reporting</ref> Saleem \u2018Kurla\u2019 in April 1998 followed by Mohammad Jindran in June 1998 and Majeed Khan on 1 March 1999 were shot dead.\n\nThe Shiv Sena, which ruled [[Maharashtra]] in a coalition with the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) from 1994 to 1999, is speculated to have sympathized with Chhota Rajan. It is reported that selective police action against the Ibrahim crime syndicate during the Shiv Sena administration and its subsequent decline through [[encounter killings]] helped strengthen Chhota Rajan's position in the underworld. This is similar to how Dawood Ibrahim himself had benefitted from the 1980s police campaign against the [[Pathans]].<ref>[https://www.pressreader.com/india/mid-day/20170623/283502206014997 Police Action During Mumbai Gang Wars] - Press Reader Reporting</ref> The Shiv Sena laid bare its affection for Chhota Rajan in an editorial in the [[Saamna]] newspaper, its mouthpiece, edited by [[Bal Thackeray]]. The editorial heaved a sigh of relief, attributing Chhota Rajan's survival to \"good fortune\" resulting from divine grace. The  Pakistani [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI) was believed to be behind the attempted assassination of Chhota Rajan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ketan.net/art1_13.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2008-10-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624012337/http://www.ketan.net/art1_13.html |archive-date=2008-06-24 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, alleged Chhota Rajan associates gunned down [[Nepal]]i media baron [[Jamim Shah]] point blank in broad daylight as he was driving to his residence on a public road.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/Indian-contract-killer-targets-Dawoods-man-in-Nepal-jail/articleshow/7670573.cms | title='Indian' contract killer targets 'Dawood's man' in Nepal jail | date=10 March 2011 | newspaper=Times Of India | accessdate=6 January 2019 }}</ref> Shah ostensibly had links with Dawood Ibrahim and was the mastermind of a racket producing [[counterfeit]] Indian currency within Nepal. His anti-Indian criminal activities had rankled the [[India]]n government for more than a decade and half prior.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/Story/83097/India/Chhota+Rajan+gang+killed+Nepal+baron.html|title=Chhota Rajan gang killed Nepal baron|newspaper=[[India Today]]|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 2006, Ibrahim's daughter, Mahrukh Ibrahim, married Junaid Miandad, the son of Pakistani cricketer [[Javed Miandad]].<ref name=BBC>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4775531.stm |work=BBC News |title=Profile: India's fugitive gangster |date=12 September 2006 }}</ref> In 2011, his daughter Mehreen, 24, married Ayub, a Pakistani-American.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-children-weddings/1/153745.html |title=Tale behind weddings of Dawood Ibrahim's children : Neighbours, News&nbsp;\u2014 India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date= |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref> His son Moin married Saniya, daughter of a London-based businessman on 25 September 2011.<ref>[http://m.indiatoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-son-moin-ibrahim-marriage/1/152976.html Dawood's son Moin marries London girl in Karachi<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Several of his family members, including his brother, Iqbal Kaskar, live in Mumbai.<ref>http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/unfair-to-deny-passport-for-being-dawoods-brother-kaskar/</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nDawood Ibrahim and his syndicate [[D-Company]] have been linked to the financing of the [[Bollywood]] film industry. A number of Bollywood studios and films were financed by D-Company in the 1980s and 1990s. Ibrahim was linked to a number of celebrities during that time, including the beauty pageant contestant Anita Ayub and the Bollywood actress [[Mandakini (actress)|Mandakini]]. D-Company is also known for extortion and threats targeted towards Bollywood producers and celebrities, and was involved in the murders of Bollywood producers Javed Siddique and [[Gulshan Kumar]].<ref>[https://www.scoopwhoop.com/inothernews/bollywood-underworld-connection/ 10 Times Bollywood Actors Crossed Paths With The Underworld], [[ScoopWhoop]], 11 August 2015</ref>\n\nThe 2002 film ''[[Company (film)|Company]]'' is based loosely on D-Company's activities, and its sequel (prequel to events in the movie), the 2005 film ''[[D (film)|D]]'', as well as ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]'' (2007) and the 2010 film ''[[Once Upon a Time in Mumbai]]''.<ref name=em>{{cite web |title=Akshay to play dreaded don Dawood? |url=http://www.emirates247.com/entertainment/films-music/akshay-to-play-dreaded-don-dawood-2011-03-07-1.364805 |date=7 March 2011|publisher=Emirates247 }}</ref> The 2013 movie ''[[Shootout at Wadala]]'' is based on the rise of the D-Company. The film ''[[Haseena Parkar]]'' (2017) is a biographical crime film based on his sister, Haseena Parkar. The 2018 video game [[Hitman 2]] features a Mumbai crime lord active in the movie industry called \"Dawood Rangan\" as a target, presumably as a reference to Ibrahim himself.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pakistan|India}}\n* [[1993 Bombay bombings]]\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[Organised crime in India]]\n* [[Tiger Memon]]\n* [[Yakub Memon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/at-home-in-exile/210415 At Home In Exile]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4775531.stm BBC Profile on Ibrahim]\n* [http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1607/16070420.htm Mumbai's Mafia War]\n\n{{Fugitives wanted by India}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Organised crime in India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibrahim, Dawood}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:1993 Bombay bombings]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Confidence tricksters]]\n[[Category:Crime in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Crime in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:D-Company]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by India]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by the United States]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on counterfeiting charges]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on organised crime charges]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on terrorism charges]]\n[[Category:Indian counterfeiters]]\n[[Category:Indian drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:Indian expatriates in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Indian expatriates in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Indian mob bosses]]\n[[Category:Indian money launderers]]\n[[Category:Indian smugglers]]\n[[Category:Konkani Muslims]]\n[[Category:Organised crime in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:People sanctioned under the Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designation Act]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mumbai monster, drug dealer, and terrorist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{cleanup|reason=conflicting places of birth.|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Dawood Ibrahim \n| image = \n| birth_name = Dawood Ibrahim Kaskar\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1955|12|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Khed, Ratnagiri|Khed]], [[Bombay State]], India\n\n \n| occupation = Gangster and drug dealer\n| organization = [[D-Company]]\n| net_worth = {{Estimation}} US$ 200 million (May 2015)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dawood Ibrahim is the 2nd richest gangster of all time|url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-pakistan-karachi/1/941579.html|website=[[India Today]]|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n| spouse = Mehjabeen Shaikh (aka Zubeena Zareen)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/its-official-again-ahead-of-nsa-talks-fresh-photo-passport-copy-of-dawood-confirm-hes-in-pakistan-2403302.html|title=It is official: Ahead of NSA meet, fresh photo and passport copy of Dawood Ibrahim confirm he's in Pakistan|work=Firstpost}}</ref>\n| criminal_charge = [[Organised crime]], [[drug trafficking]], [[extortion]], [[targeted killing]], [[terrorism]]\n| wanted_by = India\n| wanted_since = 1994\n| opponents = {{Collapsible list\n|title = At least 4\n| 1 = [[Gang wars between Chota Rajan and Dawood Ibrahim|Rajan Nikalje]]\n| 2 = [[Ali Budesh#Open war with Dawood Ibrahim|Ali Budesh]]\n| 3 = Ejaz Lakdawal\n| 4 = [[Arun Gawli#Criminal activities|Arun Gawli]]\n}}\n| children = 3\n| relatives = [[Shabir Ibrahim Kaskar]] (brother); (deceased)<br />Iqbal Ibrahim Kaskar (brother)<br />[[Haseena Parkar]] (sister);(deceased)\n| nationality = Indian\n}}\n'''Dawood Ibrahim Kaskar''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-us-Dawood_Ibrahim_from_India_pronunciation_(Voice_of_America).ogg |\u026a|b|r|\u0259|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|m}}; born 26 December 1955) is a [[Organised crime in India#Mumbai underworld|Mumbai underworld figure]], criminal mobster and drug dealer most wanted by India with a reward of $25 million<ref name=\"reward\">{{cite web|title=3 students forced to end their 'Dawood hunt' after money runs out|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/3-students-forced-to-end-their-dawood-hunt-after-money-runs-out-1373291.html/amp|website=[[First Post]]|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> over his head, and has been wanted since 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://keralakaumudi.com/en/news/news.php?id=111752&u=new-evidence-proves-dawood-ibrahim-hiding-in-pakistans-karachi-111752|title=New evidence proves Dawood Ibrahim hiding in Pakistan's Karachi|last=Daily|first=Keralakaumudi|website=Keralakaumudi Daily|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> He is originally from [[Dongri]] in [[Mumbai]], India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/jl9742.aspx|title=Treasury Sanctions Two Indian Nationals and a Company Based in Pakistan for Ties to the South Asian Criminal Network \u2018D Company\u2019|website=www.treasury.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sc/suborg/en/sanctions/1267/aq_sanctions_list/summaries/individual/dawood-ibrahim-kaskar|title=DAWOOD IBRAHIM KASKAR {{!}} United Nations Security Council Subsidiary Organs|website=www.un.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently believed to be residing in Pakistan, according to the Indian government,<ref name=\"ind-exp-inpakistan\"/> and heads the Indian [[organised crime]] syndicate [[D-Company]] which he founded in [[Mumbai]] in the 1970s.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/article3093209.ece The name on the Mumbai street over terror attacks is Dawood Ibrahim.] ''The Times''. 13 July 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim Kaskar |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/dawood-ibrahim-kaskar/|newspaper=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/international/21583285-growth-slows-and-reforms-falter-economic-activity-shifting-out-india-made-outside|title=Made outside India|website=The Economist|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/24/opinion/fix-the-link-to-pakistan-bond-with-india.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Fix the Link to Pakistan, Bond With India|last=Kugelman|first=Michael|date=2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/dec/02/mumbai-most-wanted|title=India names two most-wanted fugitives after Mumbai attacks|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=2008-12-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Dawood is wanted on the charges of [[murder]], [[extortion]], [[targeted killing]], [[drug trafficking]], [[terrorism]] and various other cases. He was designated as a global terrorist in 2003 by India and the United States with a reward of US$25 million for his capture for his believed role in the [[1993 Bombay bombings]].<ref name=\"reward\"/><ref name=Interpol>{{cite web |title=Shaikh, Dawood Hasan |publisher=[[Interpol]] |url=http://www.interpol.int/Wanted-Persons/%28wanted_id%29/1993-14193 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20121212010010/http://www.interpol.int/Wanted-Persons/(wanted_id)/1993-14193 |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=30 December 2012 }}</ref> In 2011, he was named number three on \"The World's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives\" by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Henley |first1=Jon |title=Who is now on the World's Most Wanted list? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/may/04/the-worlds-most-wanted-list |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> and [[Forbes]].<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2011/06/14/most-wanted-fugitives_slide_4.html \"Dawood 4th 'most wanted' criminal on Forbes list\"]. ''Forbes''. (29 April 2008). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDawood Ibrahim was born on 26 December 1955 in a [[Konkani Muslim]] family in [[Ratnagiri]] in  [[Maharashtra]], India.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 things to know about Dawood Ibrahim|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/inia-news/10-things-to-know-about-dawood-ibrahim/article1-1344167.aspx|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref>  His father, Ibrahim Kaskar, worked as a head constable with the [[Mumbai Police]] and his mother, Amina, was a homemaker.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Swami|first=Praveen|date=9 April 1999|title=Mumbai's mafia wars|url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1607/16070420.htm|journal=[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]]|volume=16|issue=7|access-date=23 August 2015}}</ref>\nHe lived in the Temkar Mohalla area of Dongri,  attended Ahmed Sailor High School from which he dropped out.\nHe grew up in the [[Dongri]] locality of Mumbai, which was when he came in contact with the gang of mobster [[Haji Mastan]], after the latter attacked two of Ibrahim's men.<ref>{{cite news|title='Dongri to Dubai,' the rise of Dawood Ibrahim|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/books/dongri-to-dubai-the-rise-of-dawood-ibrahim-484211.html|accessdate=23 August 2015|work=CNN-IBN|date=25 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIbrahim is believed to control much of the [[hawala]] system, which is the very commonly used [[informal value transfer system|unofficial system for transferring money]] and remittances outside the view of official agents. Many of the organisation's operations are in India.<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20001231/main1.htm Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2013 Main News]. ''The Tribune''. (31 December 2000). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/2002/dec/22isi.htm 'ISI pressured Dawood to carry out Mumbai blasts']. Rediff.com (22 December 2002). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Department of the Treasury]] [[Office of Foreign Assets Control#Specially Designated Nationals List|designated]] Ibrahim as a terrorist as part of its international sanctions program, effectively forbidding US financial entities from working with him and seizing assets believed to be under his control. The Department of Treasury keeps a fact sheet on Ibrahim which contains reports of his syndicate having smuggling routes from South Asia, the Middle-East and Africa shared with and used by terrorist organization [[al-Qaeda]]. The fact sheet also said that Ibrahim's syndicate is involved in large-scale shipment of narcotics in the United Kingdom and Western Europe. He is also believed to have had contacts with al-Qaeda leader [[Osama bin-Laden]]. In the late 1990s, Ibrahim traveled to [[Afghanistan]] under the [[Taliban]]'s protection. The syndicate has consistently aimed to destabilise the Indian government through riots, terrorism and civil disobedience.<ref>{{cite news |title=Possible al-Qaida link to India train attacks |publisher=[[NBC News]] |author=Robert Windrem |date=11 July 2006 |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/13815413 |accessdate=10 April 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe US stated that it will request the United Nations to list Ibrahim \"in pursuance of relevant Security Council resolutions\". Such a UN listing will require that all UN member states freeze Ibrahim's assets and impose a travel ban. Juan Zarate, the Deputy Assistant Secretary for Terrorist Financing and Financial Crimes, said that they are committed to identifying and attacking financial ties between terrorism and the underworld.<ref name=\"Rediff\"/>\nIbrahim is also suspected to have connections with terrorist organisations, and in 2002 was linked to the financing of increasing attacks in [[Gujarat]] by [[Lashkar-e-Toiba]].<ref name=\"Rediff\"/> In 2006, the government of India handed over to Pakistan, a list of 38 most wanted criminals including Ibrahim.<ref name=\"ID\">{{cite news|title=Bush administration imposes sanctions on India's most wanted criminals Dawood Ibrahim and sai bansod |publisher=IndiaDaily |date=2 June 2006 |url=http://www.indiadaily.com/editorial/9367.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212112236/http://www.indiadaily.com/editorial/9367.asp |archivedate=12 February 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 November 2006, it was reported that ten members of Ibrahim's gang were arrested by the Crime Branch of Mumbai Police. They were extradited from the [[United Arab Emirates]], from where they had been deported.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dubai extradites 10 Dawood aides |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=21 November 2006 |url=http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/nov/21arrest.htm |accessdate=10 April 2007 }}</ref>\n\n''[[India Today]]'' reported that Ibrahim provided the logistics for the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]].<ref>[http://indiatoday.digitaltoday.in/index.php?option=com_content&issueid=81&task=view&id=21254&sectionid=4&Itemid=1 India Today] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201082310/http://indiatoday.digitaltoday.in/index.php?option=com_content&issueid=81&task=view&id=21254&sectionid=4&Itemid=1 |date=1 December 2008 }}. Indiatoday.digitaltoday.in (28 November 2008). Retrieved 16 April 2012.</ref>\n\nNews media outlets reported the murder of Shiraz Asghar Ali as a sign of a dramatic shift of power between the crime lords.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vivo ipl schedule live |work=[[The Week]] |author1=Dnyanesh Jathar |author2=Quaied Najmi |date=2 February 2003 |url=http://www.the-week.com/23feb02/events11.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316063733/http://www.the-week.com/23feb02/events11.htm |archivedate=16 March 2007 |accessdate=10 April 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe Nepal government has directed freezing of assets of 224 individuals and 64 groups with Ibrahim if they are present in Nepal under Nepal's Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indistannews.com/nepal-freezes-assets-of-entities-with-dawood-al-qaeda-links/ |title=Nepal freezes assets of entities with Dawood, Al Qaeda links |publisher=Indistan News |date=26 December 1955 |accessdate=12 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229163322/http://www.indistannews.com/nepal-freezes-assets-of-entities-with-dawood-al-qaeda-links/ |archivedate=29 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, former Indian cricketer [[Dilip Vengsarkar]] alleged that in 1986, Dawood had entered the Indian team dressing room in [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]] and offered each Indian player a car if they beat Pakistan in the Sharjah Cup final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/top-stories/Dawood-entered-Indian-dressing-room-in-1986-offered-cars-to-players-Vengsarkar/articleshow/24822450.cms |title=Dawood entered Indian dressing room in 1986, offered cars to players: Vengsarkar |work=The Times of India |date=28 October 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==1993 Bombay bombings==\n{{Expand section|date=May 2017}}\nDawood is widely believed to have masterminded the [[1993 Bombay bombings|March 1993 bombings in Bombay]]. In 2003, the Indian and United States governments declared Ibrahim a \"Global Terrorist.\" The Indian Deputy Prime Minister, [[L. K. Advani|Lal Krishna Advani]] described it as a major development. Ibrahim is currently on India's \"Most Wanted List\".<ref name=\"Rediff\">{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim is a global terrorist: US |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=17 October 2003 |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2003/oct/17daw.htm |accessdate=10 April 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn a public discourse in June 2017, [[Ram Jethmalani]] confirmed that after the Bombay blasts, Dawood Ibrahim had called him from [[London]], saying that he was prepared to come to India and stand trial, on the condition that he should not be subjected to any [[Third-degree methods|third degree]] treatment from the police.<ref name=\"algebra\">{{cite web |title=The legend of Ram&nbsp;\u2013 a conversation with Ram Jethmalani |url=http://www.algebratheclub.com/event/the-legend-of-ram/ |website=Algebra talks |publisher=Algebra |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref>   Jethmalani had conveyed this to [[Sharad Pawar]], but the politicians in power did not agree to this proposal. As per Jethmalani, their refusal to allow Dawood's return was due to their fears that he would expose their secrets.<ref name=\"it\">{{cite magazine |title=Ram Jethmalani, Sharad Pawar spar over Dawood Ibrahim |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/dawood-ibrahim-surrender-ram-jethmalani-sharad-pawar-spar-280635-2015-07-04 |accessdate=13 June 2018 |magazine=India Today |date=4 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sharad Pawar: Jethmalani\u2019s proposal on Dawood Ibrahim was conditional |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/ram-jethmalanis-proposal-on-dawood-was-conditional-sharad-pawar/ |accessdate=13 June 2018 |newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nAccording to International claims, Ibrahim is believed to be living in [[Pakistan]] and then in the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.in.com/news/current-affairs/bdawood-ibrahim-was-in-pak-till-april-2013-ipl-spotfixing-chargesheetb-50243851-in-1.html |title=Dawood Ibrahim was in Pak till April 2013: IPL spot-fixing chargesheet |publisher=In.com |accessdate=12 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319043200/http://www.in.com/news/current-affairs/bdawood-ibrahim-was-in-pak-till-april-2013-ipl-spotfixing-chargesheetb-50243851-in-1.html |archive-date=19 March 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Desk |first=Web |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/588663/dawood-ibrahim-chased-out-of-pakistan-pms-special-envoy/ |title=Dawood Ibrahim chased out of Pakistan: PM\u2019s special envoy |work=The Express Tribune |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/cnnibn-videos/413193/time-crunch-10082013.html |title=Dawood Ibrahim was in Pak till April 2013: IPL spot-fixing chargesheet-CNN-IBN |publisher=IBNLive |date=10 August 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dawood-ibrahim-was-here-but-we-chased-him-out-may-be-in-uae-now-shahryar-khan/1153581/ |title=Dawood Ibrahim was here but we chased him out, may be in UAE now: Shahryar Khan |work=The Indian Express |date=10 August 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2014}}</ref> According to Indian claims he has shifted to the Pakistan-Afghanistan border. Indian sources add that \"[[Inter-Services Intelligence]] appeared extremely wary of the new Indo-US cooperation to fight terrorism. The Inter-Services Intelligence and Dawood appear under a lot of pressure\"<ref>{{cite web|author=ET Bureau |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/44943006.cms |title=ISI shifts underworld don Dawood Ibrahim to Pakistan-Afghanistan border&nbsp;\u2014 timesofindia-economictimes |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-10-27 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref>\nOn 5 May 2015 MP [[Haribhai Chaudhary]] informed the [[Lok Sabha]] (the [[lower house]] of India's Parliament) that the whereabouts of Ibrahim were unknown.<ref name=\"ind-exp-inpakistan\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim Whereabouts |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/videos/india/former-officers-contradict-centres-claim-of-dawood-ibrahim-being-untraceable-congress-sees-red-987622.html |newspaper=IBN Live}}</ref> However, on 11 May, [[Rajnath Singh]], the then [[Home Minister of India]], told the parliament that Ibrahim was in Pakistan and he will bring him back to India.<ref name=\"ind-exp-inpakistan\">{{cite news |title=Dawood Ibrahim is in Pakistan, Rajnath assures Lok Sabha |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/dawood-ibrahim-is-in-pakistan-rajnath-assures-lok-sabha/ |accessdate=19 May 2015 |newspaper=Indian Express |date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood in Pakistan, Will Get Him No Matter What: Rajnath Singh in Parliament |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/dawood-in-pakistan-will-get-him-no-matter-what-rajnath-singh-in-parliament-762125 |accessdate=19 May 2015 |publisher=NDTV |date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dawood in pakistan |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/dawood-is-in-pakistan-india-will-leave-no-stone-unturned-to-bring-him-back-rajnath/article1-1345945.aspx |accessdate=19 May 2015 |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Rajnath says Dawood is in Pakistan|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-rajnath-singh-pakistan/1/437341.html |accessdate=19 May 2015 |magazine=India Today|date=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to claims of Indian news media ''[[Times Now]]'' on 22 August 2015, Dawood was in [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]. According to said media corporation, they had conversation with a woman in Karachi on August 22, 2015. Transcripts of conversations which were published on the news agency's website, in one conversation she said that she is Dawood's wife and \"he is sleeping\", while in the second conversation she said that there was no one by that name known to her.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Times News Network |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Dawoods-wife-confirms-her-husband-is-in-Karachi/articleshow/48616473.cms |title=Dawood's wife confirms her husband is in Karachi&nbsp;\u2014 The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=August 22, 2015 |accessdate=2015-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesnow.tv/videoshow/4479776.cms |title=TIMES NOW tracks Dawood Ibrahim-News-Exclusives-TIMESNOW.tv&nbsp;\u2014 Latest Breaking News, Big News Stories, News Videos |publisher=Timesnow.tv |date= |accessdate=2015-08-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824080224/http://www.timesnow.tv/videoshow/4479776.cms |archive-date=24 August 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a dossier prepared by India in August 2015, to be handed over to Pakistan, Ibrahim has nine residences in Pakistan and has three Pakistani passports which he frequently uses to travel.<ref>{{cite web|title = Dawood Ibrahim has nine residences in Pakistan, Delhi says|url = http://gulfnews.com/news/asia/pakistan/dawood-ibrahim-has-nine-residences-in-pakistan-delhi-says-1.1571342|website = gulfnews.com|accessdate = 2015-08-24}}</ref>\n\n== Search for Dawood Ibrahim ==\nHe has been on [[The World's 10 Most Wanted]] list since 2010, and third in the list,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/05/13/bin-laden-joaquin-guzman-dawood-ibrahim-business-world-most-wanted.html|title=The World's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives|last1=Vardi|first1=Nathan|website=Forbes|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref> and is designated a \"global terrorist\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2003/oct/17daw.htm|title=Dawood Ibrahim is a global terrorist: US|date=17 October 2003|work=Rediff|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref> Many attempts have been made to locate Ibrahim by the Indian intelligence agencies, [[Research and Analysis Wing]] and [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] (IB), ever since he went into hiding. His location has been frequently traced to [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]], a claim which the Pakistani authorities have frequently denied.<ref name=\"BanksNevers2007\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g2UXBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT113|title=Combating Terrorism: Strategies and Approaches|author1=William C. Banks|author2=Ren\u00e9e de Nevers|author3=Mitchel B. Wallerstein|date=1 October 2007|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4833-7092-7|page=113}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/oct/19pakpoll1.htm|title=Pakistan denies Dawood's presence on its soil|date=19 October 2007|work=Rediff|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/envoy-denies-dawoods-presence-in-pakistan/article7195012.ece|title=Envoy denies Dawood\u2019s presence in Pakistan|last1=Khan|first1=Atiq|date=12 May 2015|work=The Hindu|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-sanjay-dutt-1993-mumbai-blasts--pakistan/1/258887.html|title=Exclusive: This is where Dawood lives in Karachi. A la Osama, the Pakistanis don't know!|date=22 March 2013|work=India Today|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/raw-report-on-terrorist-dawood-pakistan-stay-shows-he-was-not-chased-out/1/298998.html|title=Pakistan's Dawood lie nailed! RAW report on terrorist's Pak stay shows he wasn't chased out of country|date=11 August 2013|work=India Today|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref> The claims were further established in August 2015, when a phone call made to his home by an Indian television channel, ''[[Times Now]]'', was answered by his wife, who confirmed his presence at their home in Karachi. The Indian intelligence agencies immediately prepared a [[Dossier criminal|dossier]] of Ibrahim which included evidence of his location in Karachi, among other evidence. It was to be presented at the [[National Security Agency]]-level talks between the two countries in the same month, which was however, called off due to political reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/dawood-ibrahim-purchased-property-close-to-bhutto-sons-house-in-2013/article7569182.ece|title=Indian dossier lists don Dawood Ibrahim\u2019s Pakistan assets|last1=Singh|first1=Vijaota|date=23 August 2015|work=The Hindu|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/india-has-evidence-of-dawood-ibrahim-living-in-pakistan-report/|title=Dawood Ibrahim\u2019s new home in Karachi near Bilawal\u2019s residence|last1=Chowdhury|first1=Sagnik|date=23 August 2013|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[India Today]]'', [[Chhota Rajan]], a former aide of Ibrahim, who he later fell out with in 1992, said that, \"He [Ibrahim] does travel out of Pakistan once in a while but Karachi is his base.\"<ref>{{cite journal|date=31 January 1996|title='I gave the instructions for Wahid's killing'|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/i-will-return-to-india-and-face-trial-but-after-teaching-dawood-a-lesson-says-chhota-rajan/1/281836.html|journal=[[India Today]]|access-date=23 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Chhota Rajan vs Dawood Ibrahim==\n[[Chhota Rajan]] is believed to have assisted intelligence agencies in getting a low down on the activities of the [[D-Company]] and its members by using his intimate knowledge of the criminal enterprise and its operations from his experience. To reinforce his reputation as a patriotic gangster don, Chhota Rajan threatened to brutally murder those accused of engineering the [[1993 Mumbai bombings]].<ref>[https://scroll.in/article/764928/the-patriotic-don-chhota-rajan-was-said-to-be-helping-india-find-dawood-ibrahim Chhota Rajan, The \u2018Patriotic Don\u2019] - Scroll.IN Reporting</ref> Saleem \u2018Kurla\u2019 in April 1998 followed by Mohammad Jindran in June 1998 and Majeed Khan on 1 March 1999 were shot dead.\n\nThe Shiv Sena, which ruled [[Maharashtra]] in a coalition with the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) from 1994 to 1999, is speculated to have sympathized with Chhota Rajan. It is reported that selective police action against the Ibrahim crime syndicate during the Shiv Sena administration and its subsequent decline through [[encounter killings]] helped strengthen Chhota Rajan's position in the underworld. This is similar to how Dawood Ibrahim himself had benefitted from the 1980s police campaign against the [[Pathans]].<ref>[https://www.pressreader.com/india/mid-day/20170623/283502206014997 Police Action During Mumbai Gang Wars] - Press Reader Reporting</ref> The Shiv Sena laid bare its affection for Chhota Rajan in an editorial in the [[Saamna]] newspaper, its mouthpiece, edited by [[Bal Thackeray]]. The editorial heaved a sigh of relief, attributing Chhota Rajan's survival to \"good fortune\" resulting from divine grace. The  Pakistani [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI) was believed to be behind the attempted assassination of Chhota Rajan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ketan.net/art1_13.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2008-10-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624012337/http://www.ketan.net/art1_13.html |archive-date=2008-06-24 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, alleged Chhota Rajan associates gunned down [[Nepal]]i media baron [[Jamim Shah]] point blank in broad daylight as he was driving to his residence on a public road.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/Indian-contract-killer-targets-Dawoods-man-in-Nepal-jail/articleshow/7670573.cms | title='Indian' contract killer targets 'Dawood's man' in Nepal jail | date=10 March 2011 | newspaper=Times Of India | accessdate=6 January 2019 }}</ref> Shah ostensibly had links with Dawood Ibrahim and was the mastermind of a racket producing [[counterfeit]] Indian currency within Nepal. His anti-Indian criminal activities had rankled the [[India]]n government for more than a decade and half prior.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/Story/83097/India/Chhota+Rajan+gang+killed+Nepal+baron.html|title=Chhota Rajan gang killed Nepal baron|newspaper=[[India Today]]|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 2006, Ibrahim's daughter, Mahrukh Ibrahim, married Junaid Miandad, the son of Pakistani cricketer [[Javed Miandad]].<ref name=BBC>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4775531.stm |work=BBC News |title=Profile: India's fugitive gangster |date=12 September 2006 }}</ref> In 2011, his daughter Mehreen, 24, married Ayub, a Pakistani-American.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-children-weddings/1/153745.html |title=Tale behind weddings of Dawood Ibrahim's children : Neighbours, News&nbsp;\u2014 India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date= |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref> His son Moin married Saniya, daughter of a London-based businessman on 25 September 2011.<ref>[http://m.indiatoday.in/story/dawood-ibrahim-son-moin-ibrahim-marriage/1/152976.html Dawood's son Moin marries London girl in Karachi<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Several of his family members, including his brother, Iqbal Kaskar, live in Mumbai.<ref>http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/unfair-to-deny-passport-for-being-dawoods-brother-kaskar/</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nDawood Ibrahim and his syndicate [[D-Company]] have been linked to the financing of the [[Bollywood]] film industry. A number of Bollywood studios and films were financed by D-Company in the 1980s and 1990s. Ibrahim was linked to a number of celebrities during that time, including the beauty pageant contestant Anita Ayub and the Bollywood actress [[Mandakini (actress)|Mandakini]]. D-Company is also known for extortion and threats targeted towards Bollywood producers and celebrities, and was involved in the murders of Bollywood producers Javed Siddique and [[Gulshan Kumar]].<ref>[https://www.scoopwhoop.com/inothernews/bollywood-underworld-connection/ 10 Times Bollywood Actors Crossed Paths With The Underworld], [[ScoopWhoop]], 11 August 2015</ref>\n\nThe 2002 film ''[[Company (film)|Company]]'' is based loosely on D-Company's activities, and its sequel (prequel to events in the movie), the 2005 film ''[[D (film)|D]]'', as well as ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]'' (2007) and the 2010 film ''[[Once Upon a Time in Mumbai]]''.<ref name=em>{{cite web |title=Akshay to play dreaded don Dawood? |url=http://www.emirates247.com/entertainment/films-music/akshay-to-play-dreaded-don-dawood-2011-03-07-1.364805 |date=7 March 2011|publisher=Emirates247 }}</ref> The 2013 movie ''[[Shootout at Wadala]]'' is based on the rise of the D-Company. The film ''[[Haseena Parkar]]'' (2017) is a biographical crime film based on his sister, Haseena Parkar. The 2018 video game [[Hitman 2]] features a Mumbai crime lord active in the movie industry called \"Dawood Rangan\" as a target, presumably as a reference to Ibrahim himself.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pakistan|India}}\n* [[1993 Bombay bombings]]\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[Organised crime in India]]\n* [[Tiger Memon]]\n* [[Yakub Memon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/at-home-in-exile/210415 At Home In Exile]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4775531.stm BBC Profile on Ibrahim]\n* [http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1607/16070420.htm Mumbai's Mafia War]\n\n{{Fugitives wanted by India}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Organised crime in India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ibrahim, Dawood}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:1993 Bombay bombings]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Confidence tricksters]]\n[[Category:Crime in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Crime in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:D-Company]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by India]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by the United States]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on counterfeiting charges]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on organised crime charges]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on terrorism charges]]\n[[Category:Indian counterfeiters]]\n[[Category:Indian drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:Indian expatriates in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Indian expatriates in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Indian mob bosses]]\n[[Category:Indian money launderers]]\n[[Category:Indian smugglers]]\n[[Category:Konkani Muslims]]\n[[Category:Organised crime in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:People sanctioned under the Foreign Narcotics Kingpin Designation Act]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n", "name_user": "122.176.68.156", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dawood_Ibrahim"}
{"title_page": "Abdalla Abdelgadir", "text_new": "{{short description|Sudanese middle-distance runner}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Abdalla Abdelgadir\n| nationality = [[Sudan]]ese\n| birth_date = {{nowrap|{{Birth-date and age|12 September 1988}}}}\n| birth_place =\n| sport = Athletics (track and field)\n| event = 800&nbsp;m and 1500&nbsp;m\n| pb = '''Outdoor:''' <br /> '''800&nbsp;m:''' 1:47.12 (2009) <br /> '''1500&nbsp;m:''' 3:38.93 (2008) <br /> '''Mile:''' 4:00.84 (2003) <br /> '''Indoor:''' <br /> '''800&nbsp;m:''' 1:48.60 (2008)\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[athletics (sport)|athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flag|Sudan}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Afro-Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2003 Afro-Asian Games|2003 Hyderabad-Secunderabad]]|[[Athletics at the 2003 Afro-Asian Games|800&nbsp;m]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Abdalla Abdelgadir''' (born 12 September 1988), also known as '''Abdalla Abdel Gadir''' ({{lang-ar|'''\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0631'''}}), is a [[Sudan]]ese [[middle distance runner]] who specializes in the [[1500 metres]].\n\n==Career==\nHe finished fifth (in [[800 metres|800 m]]) at the [[2003 World Youth Championships in Athletics|2003 World Youth Championships]] and twelfth at the [[2006 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2006 World Junior Championships]]. He won the gold medal in the 1500 m at the [[2003 Afro-Asian Games]]. He competed at the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 1500 metres|2008 Olympic Games]] without progressing to the second round.\n\n==Personal bests==\nHis personal best times are:\n*[[800 metres]] - 1:48.74 min (2004)\n*[[1500 metres]] - 3:38.93 min (2008)\n*[[Mile run]] - 4:00.84 min (2003)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n* {{World Athletics|194154}}\n* [http://www.espn.com/olympics/summer08/fanguide/athlete?id=19985 Abdalla Abdel Gadir] at ESPN 2008 Summer Olympics website\n\n==External links==\n* {{IOC profile|abdalla-abdelgadir}}\n* {{SR/Olympics|ab/abdalla-abdelgadir-1|archive=20161202194341}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abdelgadir, Abdalla}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sudanese male middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of Sudan]]\n[[Category:World Athletics Championships athletes for Sudan]]\n\n\n{{Sudan-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sudanese middle-distance runner}}\n{{Infobox athlete\n|name = Abdalla Abdelgadir\n|nationality = [[Sudan]]ese\n|sport = Track and field\n|event = 800&nbsp;m and 1500&nbsp;m\n|pb = '''Outdoor:''' <br /> '''800&nbsp;m:''' 1:47.12 (2009) <br /> '''1500&nbsp;m:''' 3:38.93 (2008) <br /> '''Mile:''' 4:00.84 (2003) <br /> '''Indoor:''' <br /> '''800&nbsp;m:''' 1:48.60 (2008)\n|medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's Athletics}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flag|Sudan}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Afro-Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2003 Afro-Asian Games|2003 Hyderabad-Secunderabad]]|[[Athletics at the 2003 Afro-Asian Games|Men's 800&nbsp;m]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Abdalla Abdelgadir''' (born 12 September 1988) is a [[Sudan]]ese [[middle distance runner]] who specializes in the [[1500 metres]].\n\n==Career==\nHe finished fifth (in [[800 metres|800 m]]) at the [[2003 World Youth Championships in Athletics|2003 World Youth Championships]] and twelfth at the [[2006 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2006 World Junior Championships]]. He won the gold medal in the 1500 m at the [[2003 Afro-Asian Games]]. He competed at the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 1500 metres|2008 Olympic Games]] without progressing to the second round.\n\n==Personal Bests==\nHis personal best times are:\n*[[800 metres]] - 1:48.74 min (2004)\n*[[1500 metres]] - 3:38.93 min (2008)\n*[[Mile run]] - 4:00.84 min (2003)\n\n==References==\n*{{IAAF name|id=194154}}\n<references/>\n<br>\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abdelgadir, Abdalla}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sudanese male middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of Sudan]]\n[[Category:World Athletics Championships athletes for Sudan]]\n{{Sudan-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update infobox and text, add links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdalla_Abdelgadir"}
{"title_page": "The Big Red One", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Big Red One\n| image          = Big red one post.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Samuel Fuller]]\n| producer       = Gene Corman\n| writer         = Samuel Fuller\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Lee Marvin]]|[[Mark Hamill]]|[[Robert Carradine]]|[[Bobby Di Cicco]]|[[Kelly Ward]]|[[Siegfried Rauch]]|[[St\u00e9phane Audran]]}}\n| cinematography = [[Adam Greenberg (cinematographer)|Adam Greenberg]]\n| music          = Dana Kaproff\n| editing        = [[Morton Tubor]]\n| studio         = [[Lorimar]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = July 18, 1980\n| runtime        = 113 minutes (original theatrical release);<br>160 minutes (restored version)\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $4 million\n| gross          = $7.2 million<ref>{{Mojo title|bigredone}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Big Red One''''' is a 1980 [[Epic film|epic]] [[war film]] written and directed by [[Samuel Fuller]] starring [[Lee Marvin]] alongside an ensemble supporting cast including [[Mark Hamill]], [[Robert Carradine]], [[Siegfried Rauch]], [[Bobby Di Cicco]], and [[Kelly Ward]].\n\nBased on Fuller's own experiences, it was produced independently on a lower budget, shot on location in [[Israel]] as a cost-saving measure. It was heavily cut on its original release, but a restored version, ''The Big Red One: The Reconstruction'', premi\u00e8red at the [[2004 Cannes Film Festival]], seven years after Fuller's death. Fuller wrote a book, with the same title, which was more a companion novel than a [[novelization]] of the film, although it features many of the scenes that were originally cut.\n\n==Background==\n[[Image:USArmy First Inf Patch.jpg|thumb|right|Patch of the United States Army's 1st Infantry Division.]]\nFuller was a [[World War II]] veteran and served with the [[1st Infantry Division (United States)|1st Infantry Division]], which is nicknamed ''The Big Red One'' for the red numeral \"1\" on the Division's shoulder patch. He received the [[Silver Star]], [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] and [[Purple Heart]] during his service. He was present at the liberation of the [[Sokolov, Czech Republic|Falkenau concentration camp]].<ref name=\"Fuller, Samuel 2002\"/>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, the plot summary should be 400-700 words. -->\nIn November 1918, a private ([[Lee Marvin]]), using his [[trench knife]], slays a German soldier, who was approaching with his arms raised and speaking [[German language|German]]. When he returns to his company's headquarters, the private is told that the \"war's been over for four hours.\"\n\nIn November 1942, the soldier, now a sergeant in the \"Big Red One,\" leads his squad of infantrymen through [[Operation Torch|North Africa]]; they are initially fired on by a [[Vichy France|Vichy French]] general, who is then overpowered by his French troops who are loyal to [[Free France]]. Over the next two years, the squad serves in campaigns in [[Allied invasion of Sicily|Sicily]], where they are given intelligence by Matteo (Matteo Zoffoli), who informed them the location of a [[Tiger I]] [[Heavy tank|tank]] and fed by grateful Sicilian women, [[Omaha Beach]] at the start of the [[Normandy landings|Normandy Campaign]], the [[Operation Overlord|liberation of France]], where they battle Germans inside a mental asylum, and the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany|invasion of western Germany]].\n\nThe sergeant's German counterpart, Schroeder ([[Siegfried Rauch]]), participates in many of the same battles and displays a ruthless loyalty to [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] and [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]. At different times, he and the sergeant express the same sentiment that soldiers are killers, but not murderers.\n\nDuring the advance across northern [[France]], the squad crosses the same field where the sergeant killed the surrendering German, where a memorial now stands.\n\nThe squad's final action in the war is the liberation of Falkenau [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration camp]] in [[Czechoslovakia]]. Shortly after this, the sergeant is in a forest at night, having just buried a young boy he had befriended earlier after liberating the camp. Schroeder approaches, attempting to surrender, but the sergeant stabs him. His squad then arrives, and informs him that the \"war's been over for four hours.\" This time, as the squad walks away, Pvt. Griff ([[Mark Hamill]]), notices that Schroeder is still alive; the sergeant and his men work frantically to save his life as they return to their encampment.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Lee Marvin]] as The Sergeant\n* [[Mark Hamill]] as Pvt. Griff\n* [[Robert Carradine]] as Pvt. Zab\n* [[Bobby Di Cicco]] as Pvt. Vinci\n* [[Kelly Ward]] as Pvt. Johnson\n* [[Siegfried Rauch]] as [[Feldwebel]] Schroeder\n* [[Marthe Villalonga]] as Madame Marbaise\n* [[St\u00e9phane Audran]] as Walloon fighter\n* [[Perry Lang]] as Pvt. Kaiser\n* Matteo Zoffoli as Matteo\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[Warner Bros.]] was interested in filming ''The Big Red One'' in the late 1950s, sending Fuller on a trip to Europe to scout locations. Fuller directed ''[[Merrill's Marauders (film)|Merrill's Marauders]]'' as a [[Dry Run (testing)|dry run]] for the film. When Fuller argued with [[Jack L. Warner]] and his studio over cuts they made to ''Merrill's Marauders'', the plans for ''The Big Red One'' were dropped.<ref name=\"Fuller, Samuel 2002\">Fuller, Samuel. ''A Third Face''. Alfred A. Knopf (2002)</ref>\n\nIn the project's early stages, at [[Jack L. Warner]]'s urging [[John Wayne]] was lined up to play the sergeant, but Fuller felt that he was not right for the role.<ref name=\"Fuller, Samuel 2002\"/>\n\n[[Peter Bogdanovich]] helped set up the film at Paramount Pictures, which paid Fuller to write a script. However, when Paramount head Frank Yablans left the studio, the project was in [[Turnaround (filmmaking)|turnaround]]. It shifted over to Lorimar with Bogdanovich to produce (he says Fuller wanted him to play the Robert Carradine part) but then Bogdanovich pulled out and brought in Gene Corman to produce.<ref name=\"peter\">[http://www.nbrmp.org/features/PeterBogdanovich.cfm John Gallagher, \"Between Action and Cut\", August 2004] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121206113712/http://www.nbrmp.org/features/PeterBogdanovich.cfm |date=2012-12-06 }} accessed 3 June 2013</ref>\n\n=== The Reconstruction ===\nThe restored version, dubbed \"The Reconstruction,\" adds 47 minutes to the film's running time, bringing it much closer to the form Fuller imagined before the studio took it away from him.<ref name=Crust /> Film critic [[Richard Schickel]] \u2014 who praised the 1980 version in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine when it was released{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} \u2014 took the lead on the restoration, which relied on footage found in an old Warner Bros. vault in Kansas City. He was aided by editor Bryan McKenzie and Bogdanovich.<ref name=Crust>Crust, Kevin. [http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jan/21/entertainment/et-bigred21 \"'Big Red' given epic reworking,\"] ''Los Angeles Times'' (January 21, 2005).</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was entered into the [[1980 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1834/year/1980.html|title=Festival de Cannes: The Big Red One|accessdate=2009-05-25|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n===Critical reception===\nThe review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 90% approval rating with an average rating of 7.8/10, based on 48 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Big Red One|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/big_red_one/|website=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> For \"The Reconstruction\" cut, [[Metacritic]] assigned a score of 77 out of 100, based on 19 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-big-red-one|title=The Big Red One (re-release)|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his review of the original, theatrical version of the film, [[Roger Ebert]] gave it a three out of four star rating, and wrote: <blockquote>While this is an expensive epic, he hasn't fallen to the temptations of the epic form. He doesn't give us a lot of phony meaning, as if to justify the scope of the production. There aren't a lot of deep, significant speeches. In the ways that count, \"The Big Red One\" is still a B-movie&nbsp;\u2013 hard-boiled, filled with action, held together by male camaraderie, directed with a lean economy of action. It's one of the most expensive B-pictures ever made, and I think that helps it fit the subject. \"A\" war movies are about War, but \"B\" war movies are about soldiers.<ref name=\"EbertReview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-big-red-one-1980 |title=Review: The Big Red One|work=Chicago Sun-Times|author=Ebert, Roger}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn November 21, 2004, Ebert gave the film a four out of four star rating, and added it to his list of \"great movies\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-the-big-red-one-1980|title=The Big Red One Movie Review & Film Summary (1980) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-10}}</ref>\n\n''The Big Red One'' ranks 483rd on ''[[Empire magazine|Empire]]'' magazine's 2008 list of the 500 greatest movies of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/4.asp|title=Empire's 500 Greatest Movies Of All Time|publisher=[[Empire Online]]|date=2006-12-05|accessdate=2012-12-09}}</ref> Terry Lawson of the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' called it the greatest war movie of all time.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n*''The Fighting First: The Untold Story of The Big Red One on D-Day'' by Flint Whitlock&nbsp;\u2013 2004. {{ISBN|0-8133-4218-X}}\n*''The Big Red One'' (novel version) by Samuel Fuller&nbsp;\u2013 1980; republished in 2004.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0080437|title=The Big Red One}}\n* {{Amg movie|5460|The Big Red One}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=611836}}\n* [https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/big_red_one/ ''The Big Red One'' on Rotten Tomatoes]\n* [http://unlikelystories.org/06/schneider1206b.shtml Review of the Reconstruction]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3620418/Sam-Fullers-last-testament.html Sam Fuller's Last Testament]\n* [http://www.lawyersgunsmoneyblog.com/2011/06/d-day-67-years-on \"D-Day 67 Years On\" by Robert Farley on ''Lawyers, Guns and Money'']&nbsp;\u2013 June 6, 2011 Video Interview of Mark Hamill on his meeting with director [[Sam Fuller]]\n{{Operation Overlord}}\n{{Samuel Fuller}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Red One, The}}\n[[Category:1980 films]]\n[[Category:1980s war films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:North African Campaign films]]\n[[Category:Italian Campaign of World War II films]]\n[[Category:Operation Overlord films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Samuel Fuller]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Gene Corman]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Big Red One\n| image          = Big red one post.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Samuel Fuller]]\n| producer       = Gene Corman\n| writer         = Samuel Fuller\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Lee Marvin]]|[[Mark Hamill]]|[[Robert Carradine]]|[[Bobby Di Cicco]]|[[Kelly Ward]]|[[Siegfried Rauch]]|[[St\u00e9phane Audran]]}}\n| cinematography = [[Adam Greenberg (cinematographer)|Adam Greenberg]]\n| music          = Dana Kaproff\n| editing        = [[Morton Tubor]]\n| studio         = [[Lorimar]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = July 18, 1980\n| runtime        = 113 minutes (original theatrical release);<br>160 minutes (restored version)\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $4 million\n| gross          = $7.2 million<ref>{{Mojo title|bigredone}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Big Red One''''' is a 1980 [[Epic film|epic]] [[war film]] written and directed by [[Samuel Fuller]] starring [[Lee Marvin]] alongside an ensemble supporting cast including [[Mark Hamill]], [[Robert Carradine]], [[Siegfried Rauch]], [[Bobby Di Cicco]], and [[Kelly Ward]].\n\nBased on Fuller's own experiences, it was produced independently on a lower budget, shot on location in [[Israel]] as a cost-saving measure. It was heavily cut on its original release, but a restored version, ''The Big Red One: The Reconstruction'', premi\u00e8red at the [[2004 Cannes Film Festival]], seven years after Fuller's death. Fuller wrote a book, with the same title, which was more a companion novel than a [[novelization]] of the film, although it features many of the scenes that were originally cut.\n\n==Background==\n[[Image:USArmy First Inf Patch.jpg|thumb|right|Patch of the United States Army's 1st Infantry Division.]]\nFuller was a [[World War II]] veteran and served with the [[1st Infantry Division (United States)|1st Infantry Division]], which is nicknamed ''The Big Red One'' for the red numeral \"1\" on the Division's shoulder patch. He received the [[Silver Star]], [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] and [[Purple Heart]] during his service. He was present at the liberation of the [[Sokolov, Czech Republic|Falkenau concentration camp]].<ref name=\"Fuller, Samuel 2002\"/>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, the plot summary should be 400-700 words. -->\nIn November 1918, a private ([[Lee Marvin]]), using his [[trench knife]], slays a German soldier, who was approaching with his arms raised and speaking [[German language|German]]. When he returns to his company's headquarters, the private is told that the \"war's been over for four hours.\"\n\nIn November 1942, the soldier, now a sergeant in the \"Big Red One,\" leads his squad of infantrymen through [[Operation Torch|North Africa]]; they are initially fired on by a [[Vichy France|Vichy French]] general, who is then overpowered by his French troops who are loyal to [[Free France]]. Over the next two years, the squad serves in campaigns in [[Allied invasion of Sicily|Sicily]], where they are given intelligence by Matteo (Matteo Zoffoli), who informed them the location of a [[Tiger I]] [[Heavy tank|tank]] and fed by grateful Sicilian women, [[Omaha Beach]] at the start of the [[Normandy landings|Normandy Campaign]], the [[Operation Overlord|liberation of France]], where they battle Germans inside a mental asylum, and the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany|invasion of western Germany]].\n\nThe sergeant's German counterpart, Schroeder ([[Siegfried Rauch]]), participates in many of the same battles and displays a ruthless loyalty to [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] and [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]. At different times, he and the sergeant express the same sentiment that soldiers are killers, but not murderers.\n\nDuring the advance across northern [[France]], the squad crosses the same field where the sergeant killed the surrendering German, where a memorial now stands.\n\nThe squad's final action in the war is the liberation of Falkenau [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration camp]] in [[Czechoslovakia]]. Shortly after this, the sergeant is in a forest at night, having just buried a young boy he had befriended earlier after liberating the camp. Schroeder approaches, attempting to surrender, but the sergeant stabs him. His squad then arrives, and informs him that the \"war's been over for four hours.\" This time, as the squad walks away, Pvt. Griff ([[Mark Hamill]]), notices that Schroeder is still alive; the sergeant and his men work frantically to save his life as they return to their encampment.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Lee Marvin]] as The Sergeant\n* [[Mark Hamill]] as Pvt. Griff\n* [[Robert Carradine]] as Pvt. Zab\n* [[Bobby Di Cicco]] as Pvt. Vinci\n* [[Kelly Ward]] as Pvt. Johnson\n* [[Siegfried Rauch]] as [[Feldwebel]] Schroeder\n* [[Marthe Villalonga]] as Madame Marbaise\n* [[St\u00e9phane Audran]] as Walloon fighter\n* [[Perry Lang]] as Pvt. Kaiser\n* Matteo Zoffoli as Matteo\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[Warner Bros.]] was interested in filming ''The Big Red One'' in the late 1950s, sending Fuller on a trip to Europe to scout locations. Fuller directed ''[[Merrill's Marauders (film)|Merrill's Marauders]]'' as a [[Dry Run (testing)|dry run]] for the film. When Fuller argued with [[Jack L. Warner]] and his studio over cuts they made to ''Merrill's Marauders'', the plans for ''The Big Red One'' were dropped.<ref name=\"Fuller, Samuel 2002\">Fuller, Samuel. ''A Third Face''. Alfred A. Knopf (2002)</ref>\n\nOriginally, [[John Wayne]] was to play the sergeant, but Fuller felt that he was not right for the role.<ref name=\"Fuller, Samuel 2002\"/>\n\n[[Peter Bogdanovich]] helped set up the film at Paramount Pictures, which paid Fuller to write a script. However, when Paramount head Frank Yablans left the studio, the project was in [[Turnaround (filmmaking)|turnaround]]. It shifted over to Lorimar with Bogdanovich to produce (he says Fuller wanted him to play the Robert Carradine part) but then Bogdanovich pulled out and brought in Gene Corman to produce.<ref name=\"peter\">[http://www.nbrmp.org/features/PeterBogdanovich.cfm John Gallagher, \"Between Action and Cut\", August 2004] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121206113712/http://www.nbrmp.org/features/PeterBogdanovich.cfm |date=2012-12-06 }} accessed 3 June 2013</ref>\n\n=== The Reconstruction ===\nThe restored version, dubbed \"The Reconstruction,\" adds 47 minutes to the film's running time, bringing it much closer to the form Fuller imagined before the studio took it away from him.<ref name=Crust /> Film critic [[Richard Schickel]] \u2014 who praised the 1980 version in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine when it was released{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} \u2014 took the lead on the restoration, which relied on footage found in an old Warner Bros. vault in Kansas City. He was aided by editor Bryan McKenzie and Bogdanovich.<ref name=Crust>Crust, Kevin. [http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jan/21/entertainment/et-bigred21 \"'Big Red' given epic reworking,\"] ''Los Angeles Times'' (January 21, 2005).</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was entered into the [[1980 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1834/year/1980.html|title=Festival de Cannes: The Big Red One|accessdate=2009-05-25|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n===Critical reception===\nThe review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 90% approval rating with an average rating of 7.8/10, based on 48 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Big Red One|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/big_red_one/|website=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> For \"The Reconstruction\" cut, [[Metacritic]] assigned a score of 77 out of 100, based on 19 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-big-red-one|title=The Big Red One (re-release)|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his review of the original, theatrical version of the film, [[Roger Ebert]] gave it a three out of four star rating, and wrote: <blockquote>While this is an expensive epic, he hasn't fallen to the temptations of the epic form. He doesn't give us a lot of phony meaning, as if to justify the scope of the production. There aren't a lot of deep, significant speeches. In the ways that count, \"The Big Red One\" is still a B-movie&nbsp;\u2013 hard-boiled, filled with action, held together by male camaraderie, directed with a lean economy of action. It's one of the most expensive B-pictures ever made, and I think that helps it fit the subject. \"A\" war movies are about War, but \"B\" war movies are about soldiers.<ref name=\"EbertReview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-big-red-one-1980 |title=Review: The Big Red One|work=Chicago Sun-Times|author=Ebert, Roger}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn November 21, 2004, Ebert gave the film a four out of four star rating, and added it to his list of \"great movies\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-the-big-red-one-1980|title=The Big Red One Movie Review & Film Summary (1980) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-10}}</ref>\n\n''The Big Red One'' ranks 483rd on ''[[Empire magazine|Empire]]'' magazine's 2008 list of the 500 greatest movies of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/4.asp|title=Empire's 500 Greatest Movies Of All Time|publisher=[[Empire Online]]|date=2006-12-05|accessdate=2012-12-09}}</ref> Terry Lawson of the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' called it the greatest war movie of all time.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n*''The Fighting First: The Untold Story of The Big Red One on D-Day'' by Flint Whitlock&nbsp;\u2013 2004. {{ISBN|0-8133-4218-X}}\n*''The Big Red One'' (novel version) by Samuel Fuller&nbsp;\u2013 1980; republished in 2004.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0080437|title=The Big Red One}}\n* {{Amg movie|5460|The Big Red One}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=611836}}\n* [https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/big_red_one/ ''The Big Red One'' on Rotten Tomatoes]\n* [http://unlikelystories.org/06/schneider1206b.shtml Review of the Reconstruction]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3620418/Sam-Fullers-last-testament.html Sam Fuller's Last Testament]\n* [http://www.lawyersgunsmoneyblog.com/2011/06/d-day-67-years-on \"D-Day 67 Years On\" by Robert Farley on ''Lawyers, Guns and Money'']&nbsp;\u2013 June 6, 2011 Video Interview of Mark Hamill on his meeting with director [[Sam Fuller]]\n{{Operation Overlord}}\n{{Samuel Fuller}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Red One, The}}\n[[Category:1980 films]]\n[[Category:1980s war films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:North African Campaign films]]\n[[Category:Italian Campaign of World War II films]]\n[[Category:Operation Overlord films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Samuel Fuller]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Gene Corman]]\n", "name_user": "Ohpopshop", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction:Slightly expands John Wayne reference to better contextualize the reason for Wayne being vetted as a candidate for the sergeant role.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Big_Red_One"}
{"title_page": "Slash Coleman", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Slash Coleman\n| image = Reading Baltimore 2010.jpg\n| caption = Slash Coleman reading from \"Robot Hearts,\" at the Baltimore Book Festival in 2010\n| birth_place = [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n| othername =\n| spouse = \n| occupation = Storyteller, writer, producer\n| yearsactive = \n| website = http://www.slashcoleman.com/\n\n}}\n\n'''Slash Coleman''' (born August 13, 1967) is an American [[storytelling|storyteller]], producer, and writer who lives in New York City. The author of \"The Bohemian Love Diaries,\" a personal perspectives blogger for [[Psychology Today]], and an advice columnist at howdoidate.com known as \"Ask Uncle Slash,\" he is best known for his [[One-person show|one-man performance]]-based storytelling shows which combine clever wordplay, music, and poetic observations about family, spirituality, romantic relationships, and struggles to find a sense of home common with [[Generation X]] artists. His work is often compared to that of author [[David Sedaris]]<ref>[http://www.backstage.com/bso/content_display/reviews/ny-theatre-reviews/e3i948843d11d8858287aa671e70b19f57d \"Backstage Magazine: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\nColeman was born '''Jeffrey Mark Coleman''' in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], Virginia and raised in [[Chesterfield, Virginia|Chesterfield]], Virginia. He is a first-generation American and a third generation artist descended from a grandfather who was a dancer at the [[Moulin Rouge]] and a father, Mike Coleman,<ref>[http://www.styleweekly.com/richmond/michael-coleman-63/Content?oid=1382589 \"Style Weekly: Mike Coleman, 63\"] Retrieved on April 15, 2012</ref> who is a prolific sculptor.  His mother, Nicole, is a [[Holocaust]] survivor who was born in France. He legally changed his first name to Slashtipher with his [[barmitzva]] money to illuminate his [[Jewish]] past and to honor his grandparents who worked for the [[French Resistance]] during the war.<ref>[http://www.localkicks.com/community/news/Neon_Man_hits_Janets_Java_on_the_road_to_PBS \"Local Kicks: Neon Man Hits Road\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref>\n\nColeman spent his formative years in his father's art studio<ref>[http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2008/sep/24/c-cole_20080924-120209-ar-103478/ \"Richmond Times Dispatch: Center to Feature Artist\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130204225739/http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2008/sep/24/c-cole_20080924-120209-ar-103478/ |date=February 4, 2013 }} Retrieved on April 15, 2012</ref> learning to draw and paint. He began playing the piano at the age of five and took up the alto saxophone at [[L. C. Bird High School|L.C. Bird High School]]. Throughout his teens, he played in various alternative rock bands and went on to study [[jazz]] piano and creative writing at [[Radford University]] in Virginia, [[Middlesex University]] in London, and at [[Columbia College Chicago|Columbia College]] in Chicago where he received his master's degree. He went on to earn a degree at East-West College of the Healing Arts and furthered his studies at the Upledger Institute and [[Oregon College of Oriental Medicine]].\n\n==Television==\n\nColeman produced, wrote and starred in a [[PBS]] Special in 2008 entitled ''The Neon Man and Me''<ref>[http://styleweekly.com/ME2/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications%3A%3AArticle&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&tier=4&id=72CD483CF89D4D498817C4B1DDD72CE2 \"Style Weekly: Local Color Right After Sesame Street\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.commonwealthtimes.org/2008/11/13/the-neon-man-and-me/ \"Commonwealth Times: Collaboarators Provide Intimate Glimpse of One Man Show\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref> which is a tribute to his best friend, Mark Jamison, a [[neon]] artist from [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]], Virginia who was electrocuted while hanging a neon sign. A month after Jamison died, his girlfriend discovered she was pregnant. Coleman and Jamison met at Radford University while in a jazz ensemble called Vegetation Information.<ref>[http://gazettenet.com/2007/10/20/slash-colemans-one-man-comedy-ode-friendship?SESS6f6cf81613f08ce5db25f6b0302a8a40=gnews \"Daily Hampshire Gazette: Home to Friendship\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328134346/http://www.gazettenet.com/2007/10/20/slash-colemans-one-man-comedy-ode-friendship?SESS6f6cf81613f08ce5db25f6b0302a8a40=gnews |date=March 28, 2014 }} Retrieved on April 14, 2012.</ref>\n\nThe show, which seeks to illuminate a young man's challenge with his sense of place in the world after his best friend's death, included 7 monologues about friendship and an original music score. Underwritten by The Association for Death Education and Counseling and the Wilbert Foundation, the program was distributed by (NETA) The National Education Television Alliance in 2010 and aired on PBS station nationwide until 2012.  Paul Tait Roberts was the senior producer and John Felton was the executive co-producer.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1490771/ \"Internet Movie Database The Neon Man and Me\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012.</ref> The story behind ''The Neon Man and Me'' was recorded for [[StoryCorps]] and included in the archives at the Smithsonian.<ref>[http://www.storycorps.net/blog/east-mobilebooth/roanoke-va/the-neon-man/ \"StoryCorps: The Neon Man and Me\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120912004841/http://www.storycorps.net/blog/east-mobilebooth/roanoke-va/the-neon-man/ |date=September 12, 2012 }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Performance history==\n\n===2000\u201302===\nColeman lived in Portland, OR from 1997\u20132001. There, he worked primarily as massage therapist and a visual artist, selling his paintings at the Portland Saturday Market and through galleries.<ref>[http://www.capitalfringe.org/Slash-Coleman.html \"Capital fringe Interview\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> He began hosting ''Home Grown Theatre'' out of his southeast Portland apartment. The venue showcased new work from Portland performers, musicians and filmmakers and the characters in Coleman's own performance art that would eventually become a foundation of his stage work. In 2000, he formed the production company ''About Vision Entertainment'', with [[Stash Tea]] CEO Tom Lisicki, which produced over a dozen multidisciplinary products including a line of drinking teas and educational products for the Charkas.<ref>[http://kboo.fm/node/33104/ \"KBOO Radio Stage & Studio Interview\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\n===2003\u201305===\nColeman moved to Northampton, MA in 2003 and produced his first solo show \"Love in Boxes,\" at the Northampton Center for the Arts on February 14, 2004. Coleman portrayed 6 characters in the production which chronicled a young boy named Jeffrey Rabbit who practiced a peculiar courtship ritual that involved giving women unusual cardboard boxes while struggling with his attempts at love and his anxieties about rejection. The set included hundreds of cardboard boxes. The national tour included theatres in Portland, OR, Seattle, WA, Portland, ME, and Richmond, VA.<ref>[http://gazettenet.com/2004/02/09/arts-alamanac?SESS2204e02d4b98a09b5f0e79a553dce796=gnews \"Daily Hampshire Gazette\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120708085350/http://gazettenet.com/2004/02/09/arts-alamanac?SESS2204e02d4b98a09b5f0e79a553dce796=gnews |date=July 8, 2012 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\n===2005\u201306===\nIn 2005, the death of Coleman's best friend prompted his return to his hometown of Richmond, Virginia. There he created his solo show, ''The Neon Man and Me'', as a tribute to his best friend, Mark Jamison, a neon artist from Roanoke, Virginia, known as the \"Neon Man\".<ref>[http://m.styleweekly.com/richmond/slashtipher-j-coleman/Content?oid=1371562 \"Style Weekly: Annual Arts Issue\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> The show opened at Mill Mountain Theatre in Roanoke, on October 9, 2005 and ran for three weeks.<ref>[http://www.prweb.com/releases/2005/09/prweb282997.htm \"PRWeb\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.backstage.com/bso/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002952438 \"Backstage Magazine\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120721205235/http://www.backstage.com/bso/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002952438 |date=July 21, 2012 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> It was produced by an anonymous patron. ''The Neon Man and Me'' began to tour through regional art galleries, churches, synagogues, colleges, and public schools before running on the International Fringe Theatre Festival circuit, where it opened at the San Francisco Fringe Festival in September 2005 in San Francisco, California.<ref>[http://theatreba.kattare.com/mag/article.jsp;jsessionid=BF096EEB47903DC39851E2C9D9A0695A?thispage=archives.jsp&id=300&hi=1 \"Theatre Bay Area\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> Subsequent fringe festival venues included: Washington, DC.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/24/AR2007072402365.html \"Washington Post Article about Capital Fringe Festival: \"Tough \"Broads\" All Over Town\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref> Boulder, CO<ref>[http://archive.boulderweekly.com/080907/buzzlead.html \"Boulder Weekley Buzz: On the Edge\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720000444/http://archive.boulderweekly.com/080907/buzzlead.html |date=July 20, 2011 }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref> Minneapolis, MN, Long Island, NY,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/20/nyregion/20spotli.html?_r=1 ''New York Times''] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> and [[Provincetown, MA]]. Coleman donated 100% of ticket sales either back to the Jamison family, host venues or charities and helped raise nearly $100,000 for non-profits including children's hospitals, bereavement organizations, and schools.<ref>[http://www.mnartists.org/article.do?rid=155539 \"MN Artists: Manna Fest Destiny\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009</ref>\n\n[[File:Neon man performance 2006.jpg|thumb|Neon Man on opening night at Mill Mountain Theatre]]\nIn 2006, PBS/[[WCVE-TV]] expressed interest in filming ''The Neon Man and Me'', pending Coleman's ability to raise the necessary production funding.<ref>[http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2007-07-15/news/0707160197_1_slash-coleman-neon-friend-died \"Baltimore Sun\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> With the help of a student filmmaker he met on Craigslist, Coleman created a documentary entitled ''Glow'',<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100611092121/http://rutoday.radford.edu/march08/030408.html \"RU Today\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> and began a subsequent grassroots living room tour, traveling throughout Virginia homes for the next two years and taking donations until all $65,000 of the budget was raised.<ref>[http://thestory.org/archive/the_story_868_Memories_of_48.mp3/view \"American Public Media: Dick Gordon Interview\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626073953/http://thestory.org/archive/the_story_868_Memories_of_48.mp3/view |date=June 26, 2010 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\nIn 2006, with funding from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]], Coleman created a public school curriculum entitled \"Healing Community: Helping Students Come to Terms with Tragedy, Loss, and Violence.\"<ref>[http://richmond.skirt.com/node/34548\"Skirt! Richmond: \"Slash Coleman Teaches Good Grief\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716081734/http://richmond.skirt.com/node/34548 |date=July 16, 2011 }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref> He based the curriculum on the model he used to create ''The Neon Man and Me'', then with a series of artist residencies through the Virginia Commission for the Arts, he began teaching the curriculum within the Richmond Public School system. In observance of Governor Kaine's Month of the Grieving Child, Coleman produced a tour of student monologues relating to friendship and loss that was performed at the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts.<ref>[http://www.news.vcu.edu/news/Gov_Tim_Kaine_Designates_April_Month_of_The_Grieving_Child \"Gov. Tim Kaine Designates April Month of The Grieving Child\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2008/apr/09/-rtd_2008_04_09_0119-ar-151314/ ''Times Dispatch'': \"Grieving Child\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130204143133/http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2008/apr/09/-rtd_2008_04_09_0119-ar-151314/ |date=February 4, 2013 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with his solo performance work, Coleman began to collaborate with other Richmond performers and directors in the summer of 2006. Over the next four years, he created over a half dozen burlesque shows, first with Nouvelle Burlesque<ref>[http://www.styleweekly.com/richmond/see-the-ladies-dance/Content?oid=1364462 \"Style Weekly: See the Ladies Dance\"] Retrieved on April 16, 2012.</ref> and then with his own performance troupe, The Modern Burlesque Brigade.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130201130357/http://www2.richmond.com/entertainment/2008/jun/24/sex-ed-for-dummies-ar-599778/ \"Richmond.com: Sex Ed for Dummies\"] Retrieved on April 16, 2012.</ref> These included: Ballad of the Beautiful Sex Monster, Sex Education and The Death Match of Love. Emphasizing vaudeville, physical comedy, modern dance, and live jazz, Coleman is credited{{by whom|date=June 2013}} as a writer/producer/performer with helping re-introduce burlesque back into the Richmond entertainment scene for the first time since 1978.\n\n===2007\u201308===\nBy 2007, media coverage of \"The Neon Man and Me,\" had appeared in The New York Times, The Washington Post, American Theatre Magazine and Backstage Magazine. In the spring of 2007, \"The Neon Man and Me,\" ran Off-Broadway at Teatro La Tea in New York, NY.<ref>[http://dctheatrescene.com/2007/07/26/the-neon-man-and-me/ \"DC Theatre Scene\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009</ref> Later that year, Samson Trinh (composer/saxophonist) took over as musical director and a jazz trio known as The Neon Man Band began to accompany Coleman on his tour.\n\nLater in 2007, Coleman began to explore unresolved personal themes within \"The Neon Man and Me,\" mainly around issues about identity and those regarding his family and their experience with the Holocaust. He created a solo show that revealed his own connection to this profound material. \"Slash Coleman has Big Matzo Balls.\"<ref>[http://dcist.com/2008/07/slash_coleman_has_big_matzo_balls_f.php \"DCist\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921111120/http://dcist.com/2008/07/slash_coleman_has_big_matzo_balls_f.php |date=September 21, 2013 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> opened in Washington DC at the Warehouse Theater on July 24, 2008 and was again performed at the International Holocaust Exhibit in Richmond, VA.\n\nIn 2008, Coleman also began to publish articles and teach classes on marketing for artists which were included in the NPR series \"How Artists Make Money.\".<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111537791 \"DC Theatre Scene\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> Then, under the pseudonym, \"Mr. Fringey.\" he began collecting an extensive list of resources including reviews of fringe festivals for fellow fringe festival theatre performers which he shared on his blog called \"Fringe or Die.\"<ref>[http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/chicago-fringe-festival-theater/Content?oid=2318363 \"Chicago Reader\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref>\n\n===2009 \u2013 2010===\nIn 2009, Coleman was invited to perform at the National Storytelling Festival in Jonesborough, TN<ref>[http://www2.timesdispatch.com/entertainment/2011/jul/24/tdflair01-tough-act-to-follow-ar-1185593/ \"Richmond Times Dispatch: A Hard Act to Follow\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130204095105/http://www2.timesdispatch.com/entertainment/2011/jul/24/tdflair01-tough-act-to-follow-ar-1185593/ |date=February 4, 2013 }} Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> at which time Susan O'Connor, director of programs declared herself, \"a real fan,\" of his work. Afterward, Coleman rebranded himself as a professional storyteller and began to perform exclusively on the National Storytelling Circuit.\n\n\"Chaidentity\" opened on July 9, 2010 at the Goethe Institut in Washington DC<ref>[http://www.showbizradio.net/2010/07/12/review-cf-chaidentity/ \"Show Biz Radio\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/fringe/2010/07/09/hip-shot-chaidentity/ \"Washington City Paper\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> and was later performed at the National Storytelling Conference.\n\nBy the end of 2010, Coleman had been invited to perform at: The Oral History Performance Conference at Columbia University, The LA Storytelling Festival, The League for the Advancement of New England Storytelling and Stonesoup Storytelling Festival.\n\n[[Image:Portland Story Theatre Performance 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Valentine's Day Performance 2012 at Portland Story Theater.]]\n\n===2010\u201311===\nIn 2011, Coleman's work gained a wider audience. Coleman was invited to participate in two artist residencies:The International Storytelling Center and Portland Story Theater. He was also invited to perform at Pete Seeger's Clearwater Festival, The Timpanogos Storytelling Conference, and Gimistory International Storytelling Festival in the Cayman Islands.<ref>[http://www.compasscayman.com/story.aspx?id=90365 \"Caycompass: Gimistory Wows Brackers\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref><ref>[https://archive.is/20120724172413/http://www.cayman27.com.ky/2011/11/29/gimistory-festival-is-back \"Cayman27: Gimistory is Back\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\nAward-winning novelist Eliezer Sobel joined Coleman on stage for a duo version of \"Chaidentity\" which included a tour through synagogues in the mid-atlantic region. Both performers explained what it was like to grow up with mothers who are Holocaust survivors.<ref>[http://www.jewishrichmond.org/local_includes/downloads/47044.pdf \"Jewish Reflector: Step Back in Time\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\n===2011\u201312===\nIn 2012, Coleman signed with Jean V. Naggar agency and moved to New York City to begin work on his second PBS special about the rebirth of storytelling in the United States.<ref>[http://www.styleweekly.com/richmond/tinker-tales/Content?oid=1602964 \"Style Weekly: Tinker Tales\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> He became a regular personal perspectives blog contributor at Psychology Today where his posts appear under the title, \"The Bohemian Love Diaries.\"  In February, Coleman's solo show \"Big Plastic Heroes: The Last American Gladiator,\" opened in Portland, OR at The Sanctuary<ref>[http://psuvanguard.com/arts/theatrical-catharsis/ \"PSU Vanguard: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref><ref>[https://archive.is/20120716043027/http://wweek.com/portland/event-88780-big_plastic_heroes.html \"Willamette Week: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.jewishreview.org/arts/Local-heroes-promoted-in-local-comic-production+ \"Jewish Review: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/big-plastic-heroes/Content?oid=5539584 \"Portland Mercury: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> and then moved to an Off-Off Broadway venue in New York City at UNDER St. Marks.<ref>[http://showbusinessweekly.com/article-2009-big-plastic-heroes.html \"Show Business Weekly\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322032006/http://showbusinessweekly.com/article-2009-big-plastic-heroes.html |date=March 22, 2012 }} Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> The production details Coleman's childhood obsession with Evel Knievel and illuminates his colorful past.<ref>[http://www.nytheatre.com/Show/Review/bigp14114 \"NYTheatre.com: Big Plastic Heroes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120906090907/http://www.nytheatre.com/Show/Review/bigp14114 |date=September 6, 2012 }} Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> In November, Coleman performed \"The Neon Man and Me,\" at the highly acclaimed Theatre Row in the heart of the New York City theatre district on 42nd Street for one night. The sold out production received the 2012 award for Best Drama by United Solo Theatre Festival. Current solo work now includes elements of theatre, storytelling and the incorporation of his skills as a pianist and guitarist.<ref>[http://psuvanguard.com/arts/love-stories-adults/ \"PSU Vanguard: Love Stories for Adults\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref>\n\n===2012\u201313===\nIn February, Coleman was invited to give a TEDTalk at Tedx MillRiver on the creative process. Entitled, \"A Moment in Rice,\" the talk chronicled Coleman's experience with the creative impulse. In March, he was invited to become a resident artist at Horse Trade Theatre Company and launched a live daytime television talk show for artists called \"Slash Wednesday,\" at UNDER St. Marks Theatre.\n\n=== 2019 ===\nIn October, Coleman visited [[St. Christopher's School (Richmond, Virginia)|St. Christopher's School]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]] and performed his famous laughter yoga for thousands of students and faculty.\n\n==Writing==\n'''Books'''\n* ''The Bohemian Love Diaries'' ([[Globe Pequot Press|Lyons Press]], 2013) {{ISBN|978-0762786985}}\n* ''L'amore ha la febbre alta'' ([[Newton Compton ]], 2013) {{ISBN| 978-8854157750}}\n* ''Is My Chakra Pretty?'' (About Vision, 2004) {{ISBN | 978-1594572234}}\n\n'''Anthologies'''\n[[Image:Storytelling 2011 cayman.jpg|thumb|right|Performance at Gimistory in the Cayman Islands 2011.]]\n* ''Circle of the 9 Muses: A Storytelling Field Guide for Innovators and Meaning Makers'' w/ David Hutchens ([[Wiley]], 2015) {{ISBN|978-1118973967}}\n* ''Book Lovers: Sexy Stories from Under the Covers'' w/ [[Shawna Kenney]] ([[Seal Press]], 2014) {{ISBN| 978-1580055291}}\n* ''Unstuck'' w/ [[Noah Scalin]] ([[Voyageur Press]], 2011) {{ISBN|0760341346}}\n* ''Robot Hearts'' w/ Cara Bruce and [[Shawna Kenney]] (Pinchback Press, 2010) {{ISBN|978-0982644508}}\n\n==Discography==\n\n* ''The Last American Gladiator'' (2011), Storytelling/Americana/Pop<ref>[http://richmondfamilymagazine.com/rfm-community/3-richmond-artists-receive-award-from-storytelling-world/ \"3 Richmond Artists Receive Award from Storytelling World\"] Retrieved on May 1, 2013.</ref>\n* ''The Neon Man and Me'' ''Soundtrack'' (2008), Americana/Folk<ref>[http://media.www.commonwealthtimes.com/media/storage/paper634/news/2009/03/19/Spectrum/the-Neon.Man.And.Me.Soundtrack.Release.Features.Former.Current.Vcu.Students-3676724.shtml \"Commonwealth Times: The Neon Man and Me Soundtrack release features former, current VCU students.\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref>\n* ''Conversations with a Southern Wonder Boy'' (2004), Americana/Folk\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===Storytelling awards===\n\n\n*Winner Chesterfield Education Foundation Bravo! Community Award. (2015). <ref>[https://www.chesterfieldobserver.com/articles/accomplished-alumni-honored-at-awards-gala/.</ref>\n*Winner Storytelling World Award for Best Action Stories for CD compilation ''The Last American Gladiator. (2013).<ref>[http://www.richmondmagazine.com/arts/blogs_thehat.php?blogID=e08246ca01dc8f52fa04e62dd78ac5d6 \"Slash Coleman's 'Gladiator' Wins Storytelling Honor\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130616051413/http://www.richmondmagazine.com/arts/blogs_thehat.php?blogID=e08246ca01dc8f52fa04e62dd78ac5d6 |date=June 16, 2013 }} Retrieved on May 1, 2013.</ref>\n*Winner Best Drama Award for Best One-Man Play for ''The Neon Man and Me'', awarded by [[United Solo Theatre Festival]]. (2012)<ref>[http://www.thefranklinnewspost.com/article.cfm?ID=23719 \"Neon Man: Show about Franklin County native wins best drama\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130615194837/http://www.thefranklinnewspost.com/article.cfm?ID=23719 |date=June 15, 2013 }} Retrieved on May 2, 2013.</ref>\n*Winner of The 2005 [[Groucho Marx|Groucho]] Award for Best One-Man Play for ''The Neon Man and Me'', awarded by the ComedySportz Improv Theater.<ref>[http://www.roanoke.com/news/roanoke%5Cwb/wb/xp-48685\"The Roanoke Times: \"Neon Man\" Play Earns Creator a Groucho Award\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120914075618/http://www.roanoke.com/news/roanoke%5Cwb/wb/xp-48685 |date=September 14, 2012 }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy awards===\n\n*US Laughter Ambassador Award, 2019\n*Finalist 17th Annual People\u2019s Choice Award for non-fiction, 2014\n*Nominated for the Cabot Community Challenge Award, 2010\n*Nominated for Virginia Governor's Award in the Arts, 2008\n*Winner of Style Weekly's Top 40 under 40 Award, 2006\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.slashcoleman.com/ Official website]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ufs4sSKSRY4/ TEDx Talk]: \"A Moment in Rice\" TEDx MillRiver\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coleman, Slash}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Middlesex University]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:Jewish comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Radford University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Jewish American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Writers from Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:American storytellers]]\n[[Category:People from Chesterfield, Virginia]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Slash Coleman\n| image = Reading Baltimore 2010.jpg\n| caption = Slash Coleman reading from \"Robot Hearts,\" at the Baltimore Book Festival in 2010\n| birth_place = [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n| othername =\n| spouse = \n| occupation = Storyteller, writer, producer\n| yearsactive = \n| website = http://www.slashcoleman.com/\n\n}}\n\n'''Slash Coleman''' (born August 13, 1967) is an American [[storytelling|storyteller]], producer, and writer who lives in New York City. The author of \"The Bohemian Love Diaries,\" a personal perspectives blogger for [[Psychology Today]], and an advice columnist at howdoidate.com known as \"Ask Uncle Slash,\" he is best known for his [[One-person show|one-man performance]]-based storytelling shows which combine clever wordplay, music, and poetic observations about family, spirituality, romantic relationships, and struggles to find a sense of home common with [[Generation X]] artists. His work is often compared to that of author [[David Sedaris]]<ref>[http://www.backstage.com/bso/content_display/reviews/ny-theatre-reviews/e3i948843d11d8858287aa671e70b19f57d \"Backstage Magazine: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\nColeman was born '''Jeffrey Mark Coleman''' in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], Virginia and raised in [[Chesterfield, Virginia|Chesterfield]], Virginia. He is a first-generation American and a third generation artist descended from a grandfather who was a dancer at the [[Moulin Rouge]] and a father, Mike Coleman,<ref>[http://www.styleweekly.com/richmond/michael-coleman-63/Content?oid=1382589 \"Style Weekly: Mike Coleman, 63\"] Retrieved on April 15, 2012</ref> who is a prolific sculptor.  His mother, Nicole, is a [[Holocaust]] survivor who was born in France. He legally changed his first name to Slashtipher with his [[barmitzva]] money to illuminate his [[Jewish]] past and to honor his grandparents who worked for the [[French Resistance]] during the war.<ref>[http://www.localkicks.com/community/news/Neon_Man_hits_Janets_Java_on_the_road_to_PBS \"Local Kicks: Neon Man Hits Road\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref>\n\nColeman spent his formative years in his father's art studio<ref>[http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2008/sep/24/c-cole_20080924-120209-ar-103478/ \"Richmond Times Dispatch: Center to Feature Artist\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130204225739/http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2008/sep/24/c-cole_20080924-120209-ar-103478/ |date=February 4, 2013 }} Retrieved on April 15, 2012</ref> learning to draw and paint. He began playing the piano at the age of five and took up the alto saxophone at [[L. C. Bird High School|L.C. Bird High School]]. Throughout his teens, he played in various alternative rock bands and went on to study [[jazz]] piano and creative writing at [[Radford University]] in Virginia, [[Middlesex University]] in London, and at [[Columbia College Chicago|Columbia College]] in Chicago where he received his master's degree. He went on to earn a degree at East-West College of the Healing Arts and furthered his studies at the Upledger Institute and [[Oregon College of Oriental Medicine]].\n\n==Television==\n\nColeman produced, wrote and starred in a [[PBS]] Special in 2008 entitled ''The Neon Man and Me''<ref>[http://styleweekly.com/ME2/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications%3A%3AArticle&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&tier=4&id=72CD483CF89D4D498817C4B1DDD72CE2 \"Style Weekly: Local Color Right After Sesame Street\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.commonwealthtimes.org/2008/11/13/the-neon-man-and-me/ \"Commonwealth Times: Collaboarators Provide Intimate Glimpse of One Man Show\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref> which is a tribute to his best friend, Mark Jamison, a [[neon]] artist from [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]], Virginia who was electrocuted while hanging a neon sign. A month after Jamison died, his girlfriend discovered she was pregnant. Coleman and Jamison met at Radford University while in a jazz ensemble called Vegetation Information.<ref>[http://gazettenet.com/2007/10/20/slash-colemans-one-man-comedy-ode-friendship?SESS6f6cf81613f08ce5db25f6b0302a8a40=gnews \"Daily Hampshire Gazette: Home to Friendship\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328134346/http://www.gazettenet.com/2007/10/20/slash-colemans-one-man-comedy-ode-friendship?SESS6f6cf81613f08ce5db25f6b0302a8a40=gnews |date=March 28, 2014 }} Retrieved on April 14, 2012.</ref>\n\nThe show, which seeks to illuminate a young man's challenge with his sense of place in the world after his best friend's death, included 7 monologues about friendship and an original music score. Underwritten by The Association for Death Education and Counseling and the Wilbert Foundation, the program was distributed by (NETA) The National Education Television Alliance in 2010 and aired on PBS station nationwide until 2012.  Paul Tait Roberts was the senior producer and John Felton was the executive co-producer.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1490771/ \"Internet Movie Database The Neon Man and Me\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012.</ref> The story behind ''The Neon Man and Me'' was recorded for [[StoryCorps]] and included in the archives at the Smithsonian.<ref>[http://www.storycorps.net/blog/east-mobilebooth/roanoke-va/the-neon-man/ \"StoryCorps: The Neon Man and Me\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120912004841/http://www.storycorps.net/blog/east-mobilebooth/roanoke-va/the-neon-man/ |date=September 12, 2012 }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Performance history==\n\n===2000\u201302===\nColeman lived in Portland, OR from 1997\u20132001. There, he worked primarily as massage therapist and a visual artist, selling his paintings at the Portland Saturday Market and through galleries.<ref>[http://www.capitalfringe.org/Slash-Coleman.html \"Capital fringe Interview\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> He began hosting ''Home Grown Theatre'' out of his southeast Portland apartment. The venue showcased new work from Portland performers, musicians and filmmakers and the characters in Coleman's own performance art that would eventually become a foundation of his stage work. In 2000, he formed the production company ''About Vision Entertainment'', with [[Stash Tea]] CEO Tom Lisicki, which produced over a dozen multidisciplinary products including a line of drinking teas and educational products for the Charkas.<ref>[http://kboo.fm/node/33104/ \"KBOO Radio Stage & Studio Interview\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\n===2003\u201305===\nColeman moved to Northampton, MA in 2003 and produced his first solo show \"Love in Boxes,\" at the Northampton Center for the Arts on February 14, 2004. Coleman portrayed 6 characters in the production which chronicled a young boy named Jeffrey Rabbit who practiced a peculiar courtship ritual that involved giving women unusual cardboard boxes while struggling with his attempts at love and his anxieties about rejection. The set included hundreds of cardboard boxes. The national tour included theatres in Portland, OR, Seattle, WA, Portland, ME, and Richmond, VA.<ref>[http://gazettenet.com/2004/02/09/arts-alamanac?SESS2204e02d4b98a09b5f0e79a553dce796=gnews \"Daily Hampshire Gazette\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120708085350/http://gazettenet.com/2004/02/09/arts-alamanac?SESS2204e02d4b98a09b5f0e79a553dce796=gnews |date=July 8, 2012 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\n===2005\u201306===\nIn 2005, the death of Coleman's best friend prompted his return to his hometown of Richmond, Virginia. There he created his solo show, ''The Neon Man and Me'', as a tribute to his best friend, Mark Jamison, a neon artist from Roanoke, Virginia, known as the \"Neon Man\".<ref>[http://m.styleweekly.com/richmond/slashtipher-j-coleman/Content?oid=1371562 \"Style Weekly: Annual Arts Issue\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> The show opened at Mill Mountain Theatre in Roanoke, on October 9, 2005 and ran for three weeks.<ref>[http://www.prweb.com/releases/2005/09/prweb282997.htm \"PRWeb\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.backstage.com/bso/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002952438 \"Backstage Magazine\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120721205235/http://www.backstage.com/bso/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002952438 |date=July 21, 2012 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> It was produced by an anonymous patron. ''The Neon Man and Me'' began to tour through regional art galleries, churches, synagogues, colleges, and public schools before running on the International Fringe Theatre Festival circuit, where it opened at the San Francisco Fringe Festival in September 2005 in San Francisco, California.<ref>[http://theatreba.kattare.com/mag/article.jsp;jsessionid=BF096EEB47903DC39851E2C9D9A0695A?thispage=archives.jsp&id=300&hi=1 \"Theatre Bay Area\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> Subsequent fringe festival venues included: Washington, DC.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/24/AR2007072402365.html \"Washington Post Article about Capital Fringe Festival: \"Tough \"Broads\" All Over Town\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref> Boulder, CO<ref>[http://archive.boulderweekly.com/080907/buzzlead.html \"Boulder Weekley Buzz: On the Edge\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720000444/http://archive.boulderweekly.com/080907/buzzlead.html |date=July 20, 2011 }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref> Minneapolis, MN, Long Island, NY,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/20/nyregion/20spotli.html?_r=1 ''New York Times''] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> and [[Provincetown, MA]]. Coleman donated 100% of ticket sales either back to the Jamison family, host venues or charities and helped raise nearly $100,000 for non-profits including children's hospitals, bereavement organizations, and schools.<ref>[http://www.mnartists.org/article.do?rid=155539 \"MN Artists: Manna Fest Destiny\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009</ref>\n\n[[File:Neon man performance 2006.jpg|thumb|Neon Man on opening night at Mill Mountain Theatre]]\nIn 2006, PBS/[[WCVE-TV]] expressed interest in filming ''The Neon Man and Me'', pending Coleman's ability to raise the necessary production funding.<ref>[http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2007-07-15/news/0707160197_1_slash-coleman-neon-friend-died \"Baltimore Sun\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> With the help of a student filmmaker he met on Craigslist, Coleman created a documentary entitled ''Glow'',<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100611092121/http://rutoday.radford.edu/march08/030408.html \"RU Today\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> and began a subsequent grassroots living room tour, traveling throughout Virginia homes for the next two years and taking donations until all $65,000 of the budget was raised.<ref>[http://thestory.org/archive/the_story_868_Memories_of_48.mp3/view \"American Public Media: Dick Gordon Interview\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626073953/http://thestory.org/archive/the_story_868_Memories_of_48.mp3/view |date=June 26, 2010 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\nIn 2006, with funding from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]], Coleman created a public school curriculum entitled \"Healing Community: Helping Students Come to Terms with Tragedy, Loss, and Violence.\"<ref>[http://richmond.skirt.com/node/34548\"Skirt! Richmond: \"Slash Coleman Teaches Good Grief\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716081734/http://richmond.skirt.com/node/34548 |date=July 16, 2011 }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref> He based the curriculum on the model he used to create ''The Neon Man and Me'', then with a series of artist residencies through the Virginia Commission for the Arts, he began teaching the curriculum within the Richmond Public School system. In observance of Governor Kaine's Month of the Grieving Child, Coleman produced a tour of student monologues relating to friendship and loss that was performed at the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts.<ref>[http://www.news.vcu.edu/news/Gov_Tim_Kaine_Designates_April_Month_of_The_Grieving_Child \"Gov. Tim Kaine Designates April Month of The Grieving Child\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2008/apr/09/-rtd_2008_04_09_0119-ar-151314/ ''Times Dispatch'': \"Grieving Child\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130204143133/http://www2.timesdispatch.com/news/2008/apr/09/-rtd_2008_04_09_0119-ar-151314/ |date=February 4, 2013 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with his solo performance work, Coleman began to collaborate with other Richmond performers and directors in the summer of 2006. Over the next four years, he created over a half dozen burlesque shows, first with Nouvelle Burlesque<ref>[http://www.styleweekly.com/richmond/see-the-ladies-dance/Content?oid=1364462 \"Style Weekly: See the Ladies Dance\"] Retrieved on April 16, 2012.</ref> and then with his own performance troupe, The Modern Burlesque Brigade.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130201130357/http://www2.richmond.com/entertainment/2008/jun/24/sex-ed-for-dummies-ar-599778/ \"Richmond.com: Sex Ed for Dummies\"] Retrieved on April 16, 2012.</ref> These included: Ballad of the Beautiful Sex Monster, Sex Education and The Death Match of Love. Emphasizing vaudeville, physical comedy, modern dance, and live jazz, Coleman is credited{{by whom|date=June 2013}} as a writer/producer/performer with helping re-introduce burlesque back into the Richmond entertainment scene for the first time since 1978.\n\n===2007\u201308===\nBy 2007, media coverage of \"The Neon Man and Me,\" had appeared in The New York Times, The Washington Post, American Theatre Magazine and Backstage Magazine. In the spring of 2007, \"The Neon Man and Me,\" ran Off-Broadway at Teatro La Tea in New York, NY.<ref>[http://dctheatrescene.com/2007/07/26/the-neon-man-and-me/ \"DC Theatre Scene\"] Retrieved on August 19, 2009</ref> Later that year, Samson Trinh (composer/saxophonist) took over as musical director and a jazz trio known as The Neon Man Band began to accompany Coleman on his tour.\n\nLater in 2007, Coleman began to explore unresolved personal themes within \"The Neon Man and Me,\" mainly around issues about identity and those regarding his family and their experience with the Holocaust. He created a solo show that revealed his own connection to this profound material. \"Slash Coleman has Big Matzo Balls.\"<ref>[http://dcist.com/2008/07/slash_coleman_has_big_matzo_balls_f.php \"DCist\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921111120/http://dcist.com/2008/07/slash_coleman_has_big_matzo_balls_f.php |date=September 21, 2013 }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> opened in Washington DC at the Warehouse Theater on July 24, 2008 and was again performed at the International Holocaust Exhibit in Richmond, VA.\n\nIn 2008, Coleman also began to publish articles and teach classes on marketing for artists which were included in the NPR series \"How Artists Make Money.\".<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111537791 \"DC Theatre Scene\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> Then, under the pseudonym, \"Mr. Fringey.\" he began collecting an extensive list of resources including reviews of fringe festivals for fellow fringe festival theatre performers which he shared on his blog called \"Fringe or Die.\"<ref>[http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/chicago-fringe-festival-theater/Content?oid=2318363 \"Chicago Reader\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref>\n\n===2009 \u2013 2010===\nIn 2009, Coleman was invited to perform at the National Storytelling Festival in Jonesborough, TN<ref>[http://www2.timesdispatch.com/entertainment/2011/jul/24/tdflair01-tough-act-to-follow-ar-1185593/ \"Richmond Times Dispatch: A Hard Act to Follow\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130204095105/http://www2.timesdispatch.com/entertainment/2011/jul/24/tdflair01-tough-act-to-follow-ar-1185593/ |date=February 4, 2013 }} Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> at which time Susan O'Connor, director of programs declared herself, \"a real fan,\" of his work. Afterward, Coleman rebranded himself as a professional storyteller and began to perform exclusively on the National Storytelling Circuit.\n\n\"Chaidentity\" opened on July 9, 2010 at the Goethe Institut in Washington DC<ref>[http://www.showbizradio.net/2010/07/12/review-cf-chaidentity/ \"Show Biz Radio\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/fringe/2010/07/09/hip-shot-chaidentity/ \"Washington City Paper\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref> and was later performed at the National Storytelling Conference.\n\nBy the end of 2010, Coleman had been invited to perform at: The Oral History Performance Conference at Columbia University, The LA Storytelling Festival, The League for the Advancement of New England Storytelling and Stonesoup Storytelling Festival.\n\n[[Image:Portland Story Theatre Performance 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Valentine's Day Performance 2012 at Portland Story Theater.]]\n\n===2010\u201311===\nIn 2011, Coleman's work gained a wider audience. Coleman was invited to participate in two artist residencies:The International Storytelling Center and Portland Story Theater. He was also invited to perform at Pete Seeger's Clearwater Festival, The Timpanogos Storytelling Conference, and Gimistory International Storytelling Festival in the Cayman Islands.<ref>[http://www.compasscayman.com/story.aspx?id=90365 \"Caycompass: Gimistory Wows Brackers\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref><ref>[https://archive.is/20120724172413/http://www.cayman27.com.ky/2011/11/29/gimistory-festival-is-back \"Cayman27: Gimistory is Back\"] Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\nAward-winning novelist Eliezer Sobel joined Coleman on stage for a duo version of \"Chaidentity\" which included a tour through synagogues in the mid-atlantic region. Both performers explained what it was like to grow up with mothers who are Holocaust survivors.<ref>[http://www.jewishrichmond.org/local_includes/downloads/47044.pdf \"Jewish Reflector: Step Back in Time\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved on April 13, 2012</ref>\n\n===2011\u201312===\nIn 2012, Coleman signed with Jean V. Naggar agency and moved to New York City to begin work on his second PBS special about the rebirth of storytelling in the United States.<ref>[http://www.styleweekly.com/richmond/tinker-tales/Content?oid=1602964 \"Style Weekly: Tinker Tales\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> He became a regular personal perspectives blog contributor at Psychology Today where his posts appear under the title, \"The Bohemian Love Diaries.\"  In February, Coleman's solo show \"Big Plastic Heroes: The Last American Gladiator,\" opened in Portland, OR at The Sanctuary<ref>[http://psuvanguard.com/arts/theatrical-catharsis/ \"PSU Vanguard: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref><ref>[https://archive.is/20120716043027/http://wweek.com/portland/event-88780-big_plastic_heroes.html \"Willamette Week: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.jewishreview.org/arts/Local-heroes-promoted-in-local-comic-production+ \"Jewish Review: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/big-plastic-heroes/Content?oid=5539584 \"Portland Mercury: Big Plastic Heroes\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> and then moved to an Off-Off Broadway venue in New York City at UNDER St. Marks.<ref>[http://showbusinessweekly.com/article-2009-big-plastic-heroes.html \"Show Business Weekly\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322032006/http://showbusinessweekly.com/article-2009-big-plastic-heroes.html |date=March 22, 2012 }} Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> The production details Coleman's childhood obsession with Evel Knievel and illuminates his colorful past.<ref>[http://www.nytheatre.com/Show/Review/bigp14114 \"NYTheatre.com: Big Plastic Heroes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120906090907/http://www.nytheatre.com/Show/Review/bigp14114 |date=September 6, 2012 }} Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref> In November, Coleman performed \"The Neon Man and Me,\" at the highly acclaimed Theatre Row in the heart of the New York City theatre district on 42nd Street for one night. The sold out production received the 2012 award for Best Drama by United Solo Theatre Festival. Current solo work now includes elements of theatre, storytelling and the incorporation of his skills as a pianist and guitarist.<ref>[http://psuvanguard.com/arts/love-stories-adults/ \"PSU Vanguard: Love Stories for Adults\"] Retrieved on April 14, 2012</ref>\n\n===2012\u201313===\nIn February, Coleman was invited to give a TEDTalk at Tedx MillRiver on the creative process. Entitled, \"A Moment in Rice,\" the talk chronicled Coleman's experience with the creative impulse. In March, he was invited to become a resident artist at Horse Trade Theatre Company and launched a live daytime television talk show for artists called \"Slash Wednesday,\" at UNDER St. Marks Theatre.\n\n=== 2019 ===\nIn October, Coleman visited [[St. Christopher's School (Richmond, Virginia)|St. Christopher's School]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]] and performed his famous laughter yoga for thousands of students and faculty.\n\n==Writing==\n'''Books'''\n* ''The Bohemian Love Diaries'' ([[Globe Pequot Press|Lyons Press]], 2013) {{ISBN|978-0762786985}}\n* ''L'amore ha la febbre alta'' ([[Newton Compton ]], 2013) {{ISBN| 978-8854157750}}\n* ''Is My Chakra Pretty?'' (About Vision, 2004) {{ISBN | 978-1594572234}}\n\n'''Anthologies'''\n[[Image:Storytelling 2011 cayman.jpg|thumb|right|Performance at Gimistory in the Cayman Islands 2011.]]\n* ''Circle of the 9 Muses: A Storytelling Field Guide for Innovators and Meaning Makers'' w/ David Hutchens ([[Wiley]], 2015) {{ISBN|978-1118973967}}\n* ''Book Lovers: Sexy Stories from Under the Covers'' w/ [[Shawna Kenney]] ([[Seal Press]], 2014) {{ISBN| 978-1580055291}}\n* ''Unstuck'' w/ [[Noah Scalin]] ([[Voyageur Press]], 2011) {{ISBN|0760341346}}\n* ''Robot Hearts'' w/ Cara Bruce and [[Shawna Kenney]] (Pinchback Press, 2010) {{ISBN|978-0982644508}}\n\n==Discography==\n\n* ''The Last American Gladiator'' (2011), Storytelling/Americana/Pop<ref>[http://richmondfamilymagazine.com/rfm-community/3-richmond-artists-receive-award-from-storytelling-world/ \"3 Richmond Artists Receive Award from Storytelling World\"] Retrieved on May 1, 2013.</ref>\n* ''The Neon Man and Me'' ''Soundtrack'' (2008), Americana/Folk<ref>[http://media.www.commonwealthtimes.com/media/storage/paper634/news/2009/03/19/Spectrum/the-Neon.Man.And.Me.Soundtrack.Release.Features.Former.Current.Vcu.Students-3676724.shtml \"Commonwealth Times: The Neon Man and Me Soundtrack release features former, current VCU students.\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref>\n* ''Conversations with a Southern Wonder Boy'' (2004), Americana/Folk\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===Storytelling awards===\n\n\n*Winner Chesterfield Education Foundation Bravo! Community Award. (2015). <ref>[https://www.chesterfieldobserver.com/articles/accomplished-alumni-honored-at-awards-gala/.</ref>\n*Winner Storytelling World Award for Best Action Stories for CD compilation ''The Last American Gladiator. (2013).<ref>[http://www.richmondmagazine.com/arts/blogs_thehat.php?blogID=e08246ca01dc8f52fa04e62dd78ac5d6 \"Slash Coleman's 'Gladiator' Wins Storytelling Honor\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130616051413/http://www.richmondmagazine.com/arts/blogs_thehat.php?blogID=e08246ca01dc8f52fa04e62dd78ac5d6 |date=June 16, 2013 }} Retrieved on May 1, 2013.</ref>\n*Winner Best Drama Award for Best One-Man Play for ''The Neon Man and Me'', awarded by [[United Solo Theatre Festival]]. (2012)<ref>[http://www.thefranklinnewspost.com/article.cfm?ID=23719 \"Neon Man: Show about Franklin County native wins best drama\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130615194837/http://www.thefranklinnewspost.com/article.cfm?ID=23719 |date=June 15, 2013 }} Retrieved on May 2, 2013.</ref>\n*Winner of The 2005 [[Groucho Marx|Groucho]] Award for Best One-Man Play for ''The Neon Man and Me'', awarded by the ComedySportz Improv Theater.<ref>[http://www.roanoke.com/news/roanoke%5Cwb/wb/xp-48685\"The Roanoke Times: \"Neon Man\" Play Earns Creator a Groucho Award\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120914075618/http://www.roanoke.com/news/roanoke%5Cwb/wb/xp-48685 |date=September 14, 2012 }} Retrieved on August 19, 2009.</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy awards===\n\n\n*Finalist 17th Annual People\u2019s Choice Award for non-fiction, 2014\n*Nominated for the Cabot Community Challenge Award, 2010\n*Nominated for Virginia Governor's Award in the Arts, 2008\n*Winner of Style Weekly's Top 40 under 40 Award, 2006\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.slashcoleman.com/ Official website]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ufs4sSKSRY4/ TEDx Talk]: \"A Moment in Rice\" TEDx MillRiver\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coleman, Slash}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Middlesex University]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:Jewish comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Radford University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Jewish American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Writers from Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:American storytellers]]\n[[Category:People from Chesterfield, Virginia]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n", "name_user": "242million", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePhilanthropy awards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slash_Coleman"