{"title_page": "Crimean Gothic", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|Gothic Germanic language variety extinct by the 18th century}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Crimean Gothic\n|states=formerly [[Crimea]]\n|ethnicity = [[Crimean Goths]]\n|extinct=by the 18th century\n|familycolor=Indo-European\n|fam2=[[Germanic languages|Germanic]]\n|fam3=[[East Germanic languages|East Germanic]]\n|fam4=[[Gothic language|Gothic]]\n|script=[[Gothic alphabet]]\n|isoexception=dialect\n|glotto=crim1255\n|glottorefname=Crimean Gothic\n}}\n'''Crimean Gothic''' was an [[East Germanic languages|East Germanic]] language spoken by the [[Crimean Goths]] in some isolated locations in [[Crimea]] until the late 18th century.<ref>{{cite web| title=The Corpus of Crimean Gothic| author=Todd B. Krause and Jonathan Slocum| publisher=University of Texas at Austin| url=http://www.utexas.edu/cola/centers/lrc/eieol/gotol-10-R.html| access-date=February 6, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302065118/http://www.utexas.edu/cola/centers/lrc/eieol/gotol-10-R.html| archive-date=March 2, 2007| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Attestation==\nThe existence of a Germanic dialect in Crimea is noted in a number of sources from the 9th century to the 18th century. However, only a single source provides any details of the language itself: a letter by the [[Flemings|Flemish]] ambassador [[Ogier Ghiselin de Busbecq]], dated 1562 and first published in 1589, gives a list of some eighty words and a song supposedly in the language.\n\nBusbecq's account is problematic in a number of ways. First, his [[informant (linguistics)|informants]] were not unimpeachable; one was a Greek speaker who knew Crimean Gothic as a second language, and the other was a Goth who had abandoned his native language in favour of Greek. Second, Busbecq's transcription was likely influenced by his own language, a [[Flemish]] dialect of [[Dutch language|Dutch]]. Finally, there are undoubted [[typographical error]]s in known extant versions of the account.\n\nNonetheless, much of the vocabulary cited by Busbecq is unmistakably Germanic and was recognised by him as such:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Crimean Gothic\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Gothic language|Bible Gothic]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[English language|English]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Dutch language|Dutch]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Low German|Low Saxon]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[German language|German]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Faroese language|Faroese]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Icelandic language|Icelandic]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Danish language|Danish]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Swedish language|Swedish]]\n|-\n![[Bokm\u00e5l]]\n![[Nynorsk]]\n|-\n| apel || apls (m.) || apple || appel \n|appel / Appel|| Apfel || epli ('potato') || epli \n|\u00e6ble\n| colspan=\"2\" |eple|| \u00e4pple ('apple')<br />apel (''[[Malus]]'') \n|-\n| handa || handus (f.) || colspan=\"2\" | hand\n|haand|| Hand || hond || h\u00f6nd \n| colspan=\"2\" |h\u00e5nd|| colspan=\"2\" | hand \n|-\n| schuuester || swistar (f.) || sister || zus(ter) \n|zus / Sester|| Schwester || colspan=\"2\" | systir\n| colspan=\"2\" |s\u00f8ster|| colspan=\"2\" | syster \n|-\n| hus || -h\u016bs (n.) || house || huis \n|hoes / huus|| Haus || colspan=\"2\" | h\u00fas\n| colspan=\"4\" |hus\n|-\n| reghen || rign (n.) || rain || regen \n|regen / reagn|| Regen || colspan=\"6\" | regn \n|-\n| singhen || siggwan (vb.) || sing || zingen \n|zingen / sing|| singen || colspan=\"2\" | syngja\n| colspan=\"2\" |synge|| syngja || sjunga \n|-\n| geen || gaggan (vb.) || go || gaan \n|gaon|| gehen || colspan=\"2\" | ganga\n| colspan=\"4\" |g\u00e5\n|}\n\n(Note:  [[Central consonant|Medial]] -''gg''- in the Biblical Gothic examples represents {{IPA|/\u014bg/}})\n\nBusbecq also cites a number of words which he did not recognise but which are now known to have Germanic [[cognate]]s:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!width=\"100\"| Crimean Gothic\n![[Gothic language|Bible Gothic]]\n! [[English language|English]]\n! [[Dutch language|Dutch]]\n![[German language|German]]\n! [[Faroese language|Faroese]]\n! [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]]\n! [[Old Norse]]\n! [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] ([[Bokm\u00e5l|BM]]/[[Nynorsk|NN]])\n! [[Swedish language|Swedish]]\n! [[Danish language|Danish]]\n! [[Old English]]\n! [[Old Saxon]]\n! [[Old High German]]\n|-\n| ano 'rooster' || hana || hen || haan || Hahn || colspan=\"2\" | hani || ha\u00f0na<br /> hani || colspan=\"3\" | hane (archaic in Swedish) || hana || colspan=\"2\" | hano \n|-\n| malthata 'said' || (unattested) || (unattested) ||&mdash;||&mdash;|| colspan=\"3\" | m\u00e6lti || m\u00e6lte || \u2020m\u00e4lde<br />\u2020m\u00e4lte || \u2020m\u00e6lte || ma\u00feelode || gimahlida || gimahalta\n<!-- Do not add German \"meldete\" and Dutch \"meldde\", for they are etymologically unrelated -->\n|-\n| rintsch 'ridge' || (unattested) || ridge || rug || R\u00fccken || ryggur || hryggur || hryggr || colspan=\"2\" | rygg || ryg || hrycg || hruggi || ruggi\n|}\n\n(Note: \u2020 archaic)\n\nBusbecq mentions a [[definite article]], which he records as being ''tho'' or ''the''. This variation may indicate either a gender distinction or [[allomorph]]y &mdash; the latter whereof would be somewhat akin to the English \"the\", which is pronounced either {{IPA|/\u00f0\u0259/}} or {{IPA|/\u00f0i\u02d0/}}.\n\n==Identification and classification==\nWhile the initial identification of this language as \"Gothic\" probably rests on ethnological rather than linguistic grounds \u2014 that is, the speakers were identified as Goths, and therefore the language must be Gothic \u2014 it appears to share a number of distinctive phonological developments with the Gothic of [[Ulfilas]]' Bible. For example, the word ''ada'' 'egg' shows the typical Gothic \"sharpening\" of [[Proto-Germanic language|Proto-Germanic]] {{nowrap|*''-jj-''}} to ''-ddj-'' (as in [[Gothic language|Ulfilian Gothic]] ''iddja'' \"went\" from PGmc. *''ijj\u0113''), being from Proto-Germanic *''ajja-''.\n\nThere are also examples of features preserved in Crimean Gothic and Biblical Gothic but which have undergone changes in West and North Germanic. For example, both Crimean Gothic and Biblical Gothic preserve Germanic {{IPA|/z/}} as a [[sibilant]], while it became {{IPA|/r/}} in all other Germanic dialects: Crimean Gothic ''ies'' and Biblical Gothic ''is'' vs. German ''er'', all meaning 'he'. Also, Crimean Gothic and Biblical Gothic both preserve the medial -''d''- in their reflexes of Proto-Germanic *''fedw\u014dr'' (stem *''fedur-'') 'four': ''fyder'' in the former and ''fidw\u014dr'' in the latter. This -''d''- is lost in all North and West Germanic languages, which have forms descending from *''feww\u014dr'' or *''feur'': Old English ''f\u0113ower'', Old Saxon ''fiuwar'', Old High German ''fior'', Old Norse ''fj\u00f3rir''.\n\nHowever, there are problems in assuming that Crimean Gothic simply represents a later stage in the development of the Gothic attested in Ulfilas' Bible. Some innovations in Biblical Gothic are not found in Crimean Gothic. For example:\n* Crimean Gothic preserves Germanic {{IPA|/e/}}, whereas in Biblical Gothic it has become {{IPA|/i/}}, e.g. Crimean Gothic ''reghen'' and ''suuester'' vs. Biblical Gothic ''rign'' and ''swistar''\n* Crimean Gothic preserves Germanic {{IPA|/u/}} before {{IPA|/r/}}, whereas Biblical Gothic has {{IPA|/\u0254/}}, e.g. Crimean Gothic ''vvurt'' vs. Biblical Gothic ''waur\u00fei''.\n\nHowever, there also seem to be developments similar to those that occurred in varieties of West Germanic, such as the change of {{IPA|/\u03b8/}} to a [[stop consonant|stop]], possibly exhibited in Crimean Gothic ''tria'' (cf. Biblical Gothic ''\u00feriu''). Several historical accounts mention similarity of Crimean Gothic to [[Low German]], as well as the intelligibility of Crimean Gothic to German speakers, with the Dutch-speaking Busbecq's account being by far the most important.\n\nThere are two alternative solutions: that Crimean Gothic presents a separate branch of [[East Germanic languages|East Germanic]], distinct from Ulfilas' Gothic; or that Crimean Gothic is actually descended from the dialect of [[West Germanic languages|West Germanic]] settlers who migrated to the Crimea in the early [[Middle Ages]] and whose language was subsequently influenced by Gothic. Both of these possibilities were first suggested in the 19th century and are most recently argued by Stearns and [[Ottar Gr\u00f8nvik|Gr\u00f8nvik]], respectively. While there is no consensus on a definitive solution to this problem, it is accepted that Crimean Gothic is not a descendant of Biblical Gothic.\n\nThe song recorded by Busbecq is less obviously Germanic and has proved impossible to interpret definitively. There is no consensus as to whether it is actually in Crimean Gothic.\n\nIn 1780, [[Stanis\u0142aw Bohusz Siestrze\u0144cewicz]], an [[Archbishop]] of [[Mogilev]], visited the southern coast of [[Crimea]] and [[Sevastopol]]. According to his account, he met some [[Tatars]] who spoke a language similar to [[Plattdeutsch]]; this was probably a form of Crimean Gothic.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_vLsPAAAAQAAJ/page/n183 ''Mithridates oder allgemeine Sprachenkunde''; 1817, S. 168]</ref>\n\n==Other sources ==\nThe only non-Busbecqian additions to this very small corpus are two potentially Crimean Gothic terms from other sources: the first is a [[proper name]], ''Harfidel'', found in a [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] inscription on a grave stone dating from the 5th century AD; the second word, ''razn'' (\"house\"), may have lived on as a loan word meaning \"roof lath\" in the [[Crimean Tatar language]].<ref>Stearns 1978: 37; quoted in Maarten van der Meer, [http://www.grin.com/de/e-book/85128/morphologie-des-krimgotischen  Morphologie des Krimgotischen. Ein Vergleich mit dem Bibelgotischen], retrieved 8 January 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 2015, five Gothic inscriptions were found by Andrey Vinogradov, a Russian historian, on stone plates excavated in [[Mangup]] in 1938, and deciphered by him and Maksim Korobov.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2015/12/25/molitvy-na-kamnyah|title=\u041c\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0432\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u043c\u043d\u044f\u0445 \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043a \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0412\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044f\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u0433\u043e\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0435|last=Nemalevich|first=Sergey|date=25 December 2015|publisher=[[Meduza]]|language=Russian|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"vinogradov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gotica.de/boranicum.pdf|title=\u0413\u043e\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0444\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u0438\u0437 \u043c\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0443\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0438|author1=\u0410. \u042e. \u0412\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432|author2=\u041c. \u0418. \u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0432|year=2016|pages=57\u201375|language=Russian}} A slightly revised German translation was published as \"Gotische Graffito-Inschriften aus der Bergkrim\", Zeitschrift f\u00fcr deutsches Altertum und Literatur 145 (2016) 141-157. [https://publications.hse.ru/en/articles/185493676 English abstract]</ref> The inscriptions were written in the second half of the 9th century or in the first half of the 10th century. \n\nOne of them is a Biblical Gothic version of [[Psalm 77]]:13. It is not included in the known manuscripts of the [[Gothic Bible]] (which mostly preserve New Testament texts), but the orthography and phrasing matches that of Wulfila's Bible. In the inscription, it is followed by a sentence which does not come from the Bible, but again copies or mimics Biblical Gothic:\n\n:\u0195as g(u)\u00fe mikils\n:swe g(u)\u00fe unsar? \u00feu\n:is g(u)\u00fe waurkjands\n:sildaleika. ainn[s]\n:ussto\u00fe\n:und aiwins\n:us dau\u00feaum\n:jah in midjun[gard-]\n\n\"Who is so great a God as our God? Thou art the God that doest wonders. \nOne rose in eternity from the dead and in the world ...\"\n\nThe [[Mangup inscriptions]] may be viewed as a translation of a Byzantine formula.<ref name=\"vinogradov\"/>\n \n:f(rauj)a hilp skalkis \u00feei[nis]\n:damja[na]us us w(e)inag[ardjam ?]\n:jah frawaur(h)tis\n\n\"Lord, help your servant [[Damian (given name)|Damjanus]] from [the] viney[ard?] and the sinner\"\n\n== References ==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* MacDonald Stearns, ''Crimean Gothic. Analysis and Etymology of the Corpus'', Saratoga 1978. Includes Latin text of Busbecq's report and English translation.\n* MacDonald Stearns, \"Das Krimgotische\". In: Heinrich Beck (ed.), ''Germanische Rest- und Tr\u00fcmmersprachen'', Berlin/New York 1989, 175-194.\n* [[Ottar Gr\u00f8nvik]], ''Die dialektgeographische Stellung des Krimgotischen und die krimgotische cantilena'', Oslo 1983.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/texte/etcs/germ/got/krimgot/krimg.htm?krimg001.htm Busbecq's account, in Latin]\n* [https://lrc.la.utexas.edu/eieol/gotol Gothic Online] by Todd B. Krause and Jonathan Slocum, free online lessons at the [https://liberalarts.utexas.edu/lrc Linguistics Research Center] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]], contains a [https://lrc.la.utexas.edu/eieol/gotol/100 lesson on Crimean Gothic]\n* [http://www.gotica.de/taurica.html  Editions and Critical Studies], bibliography by Christian T. Petersen\n\n{{Germanic languages}}\n{{Germanic philology}}\n\n[[Category:Gothic language]]\n[[Category:Crimean Goths|Gothic, Crimean]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of Europe]]\n[[Category:Languages extinct in the 18th century]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|Gothic Germanic language variety extinct by the 18th century}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Crimean Gothic\n|states=formerly [[Crimea]]\n|ethnicity = [[Crimean Goths]]\n|extinct=by the 18th century\n|familycolor=Indo-European\n|fam2=[[Germanic languages|Germanic]]\n|fam3=[[East Germanic languages|East Germanic]]\n|fam4=[[Gothic language|Gothic]]\n|script=[[Gothic alphabet]]\n|isoexception=dialect\n|glotto=crim1255\n|glottorefname=Crimean Gothic\n}}\n'''Crimean Gothic''' was an [[East Germanic languages|East Germanic]] language spoken by the [[Crimean Goths]] in some isolated locations in [[Crimea]] until the late 18th century.<ref>{{cite web| title=The Corpus of Crimean Gothic| author=Todd B. Krause and Jonathan Slocum| publisher=University of Texas at Austin| url=http://www.utexas.edu/cola/centers/lrc/eieol/gotol-10-R.html| access-date=February 6, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302065118/http://www.utexas.edu/cola/centers/lrc/eieol/gotol-10-R.html| archive-date=March 2, 2007| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Attestation==\nThe existence of a Germanic dialect in Crimea is noted in a number of sources from the 9th century to the 18th century. However, only a single source provides any details of the language itself: a letter by the [[Flemings|Flemish]] ambassador [[Ogier Ghiselin de Busbecq]], dated 1562 and first published in 1589, gives a list of some eighty words and a song supposedly in the language.\n\nBusbecq's account is problematic in a number of ways. First, his [[informant (linguistics)|informants]] were not unimpeachable; one was a Greek speaker who knew Crimean Gothic as a second language, and the other was a Goth who had abandoned his native language in favour of Greek